if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['oph_p2_vitreo_retina']=[
  {q:"A 65-year-old hypertensive man presents with sudden painless severe loss of vision in one eye for 2 hours. Fundus examination reveals retinal whitening with a cherry-red spot at the macula. Which artery is most likely occluded?",o:["Central retinal artery","Posterior ciliary artery","Ophthalmic artery","Lacrimal artery","Short ciliary artery"],a:0,e:"Central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO) classically presents with sudden profound painless monocular visual loss accompanied by retinal pallor and a cherry-red macular spot due to intact choroidal circulation beneath the fovea.<br><br>Immediate management includes ocular massage, lowering intraocular pressure, and urgent stroke risk assessment. Recognising the cherry-red spot and instituting immediate measures within the narrow therapeutic window is a classic FCPS emergency scenario.<br><br>Posterior ciliary artery occlusion mainly affects choroid and optic nerve circulation. Ophthalmic artery occlusion produces more extensive ischemia with absent choroidal perfusion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO) most classically demonstrates which fundus appearance?",o:["Blood and thunder appearance","Salt-and-pepper retina","Cherry-red spot only","Bone-spicule pigmentation","Macular star"],a:0,e:"CRVO produces widespread retinal hemorrhages, venous engorgement, cotton wool spots, and disc edema, collectively called the \"blood and thunder\" appearance.<br><br>Visual prognosis depends largely on ischemic versus non-ischemic status.<br><br>Bone-spicule pigmentation occurs in retinitis pigmentosa, while cherry-red spot is typical of CRAO.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old diabetic patient presents with sudden painless unilateral vision loss. Fundus examination shows multiple dot-blot hemorrhages confined to one retinal quadrant with dilated tortuous veins. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Central retinal vein occlusion","Branch retinal vein occlusion","Hypertensive retinopathy","Retinal detachment"],a:2,e:"Branch retinal vein occlusion (BRVO) typically affects a sector of retina drained by the involved vein, producing localized hemorrhages and venous tortuosity.<br><br>It commonly occurs at arteriovenous crossing points and is strongly associated with hypertension and diabetes. Distinguishing ischaemic from non-ischaemic occlusion carries major prognostic weight and is a frequently tested clinical decision point.<br><br>CRVO affects all four quadrants diffusely. Retinal detachment presents with elevated detached retina rather than sectoral vascular hemorrhages.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of visual loss in branch retinal vein occlusion is:",o:["Vitreous hemorrhage","Retinal detachment","Optic atrophy","Macular edema","Choroidal rupture"],a:3,e:"Macular edema is the leading cause of reduced vision in BRVO and CRVO because vascular leakage disrupts central retinal architecture.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy is now first-line management in many cases.<br><br>Retinal detachment and optic atrophy are much less common causes of early visual loss in BRVO.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO undergoes fundoscopy shortly after symptom onset. Which finding may be absent during the first few minutes?",o:["Retinal whitening","Cherry-red spot","Relative afferent pupillary defect","Venous tortuosity","Sudden vision loss"],a:0,e:"Immediately after CRAO onset, retinal whitening may not yet have developed because ischemic edema requires some time to become clinically visible.<br><br>However, sudden visual loss and RAPD occur early.<br><br>Venous tortuosity is more typical of retinal vein occlusion rather than arterial occlusion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular disorder is most strongly associated with neovascular glaucoma?",o:["Ischemic central retinal vein occlusion","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Dry age-related macular degeneration","Retinitis pigmentosa","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"Ischemic CRVO causes profound retinal ischemia, stimulating VEGF production and neovascularization of iris and angle, leading to neovascular glaucoma.<br><br>Regular gonioscopy and follow-up are essential.<br><br>Dry ARMD and central serous chorioretinopathy do not usually induce severe retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with amaurosis fugax is at highest risk of developing:",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Retinitis pigmentosa","Retinal detachment","Macular degeneration","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Amaurosis fugax represents transient retinal ischemia, often embolic in origin, and may precede permanent CRAO or cerebrovascular stroke.<br><br>Carotid artery evaluation is mandatory in these patients.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa and retinal detachment are unrelated degenerative disorders rather than embolic ischemic events.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Cotton wool spots seen in retinal vascular disease represent:",o:["Lipid exudation","Retinal nerve fiber layer infarcts","Choroidal neovascularization","Vitreous degeneration","Pigment epithelial hypertrophy"],a:1,e:"Cotton wool spots are microinfarctions of the retinal nerve fiber layer caused by focal ischemia and interrupted axoplasmic flow.<br><br>They are common in diabetes, hypertension, and retinal vein occlusions.<br><br>Hard exudates represent lipid leakage rather than infarction. Vitreous degeneration does not produce cotton wool spots.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site for branch retinal vein occlusion is:",o:["Arteriovenous crossing","Optic disc margin","Macular center","Ora serrata","Foveal avascular zone"],a:0,e:"BRVO typically occurs where a thickened retinal artery compresses the adjacent vein at an arteriovenous crossing site.<br><br>This mechanical compression predisposes to venous thrombosis.<br><br>The foveal avascular zone lacks major retinal vessels and therefore is not the usual site.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe carotid artery disease develops venous stasis retinopathy. Which symptom is most characteristic?",o:["Gradual visual decline with dilated retinal veins","Painful red eye only","Sudden photophobia only","Corneal edema alone","Retinal detachment symptoms only"],a:0,e:"Venous stasis retinopathy occurs secondary to chronic ocular ischemia from carotid insufficiency and produces venous dilation, hemorrhages, and gradual visual decline.<br><br>It may progress to ocular ischemic syndrome.<br><br>Painful red eye is not the dominant feature initially. Retinal detachment symptoms are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 72-year-old patient with giant cell arteritis suddenly loses vision in one eye. Which retinal vascular event is most likely responsible?",o:["Branch retinal vein occlusion","Central retinal artery occlusion","Macular edema only","Retinal dialysis","Vitreomacular traction"],a:1,e:"Giant cell arteritis can involve ophthalmic and retinal arteries, causing arteritic CRAO and profound sudden vision loss.<br><br>Immediate systemic corticosteroid therapy is critical to protect the fellow eye.<br><br>Retinal dialysis and vitreomacular traction are unrelated vitreoretinal disorders.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hypertensive retinopathy develops macular star formation due to:",o:["Retinal detachment","Lipid exudation around macula","Vitreous hemorrhage","Choroidal rupture","Optic nerve edema only"],a:1,e:"Macular star results from hard exudates arranged radially around the macula due to leakage from damaged retinal vessels.<br><br>It is classically associated with severe hypertension and neuroretinitis. The macular star with disc oedema is a hallmark presentation worth recognising instantly in examinations.<br><br>Retinal detachment and vitreous hemorrhage do not produce radial lipid star patterns.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most useful for detecting retinal capillary non-perfusion in CRVO?",o:["Fundus fluorescein angiography","Ultrasonography","Keratometry","Schiotz tonometry","Pachymetry"],a:0,e:"FFA demonstrates areas of capillary dropout, delayed perfusion, and retinal ischemia in retinal vascular occlusive disease.<br><br>It helps distinguish ischemic from non-ischemic CRVO.<br><br>Ultrasonography is useful mainly when media opacity prevents retinal visualization.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal artery occlusion most commonly develops visual loss because of ischemia involving the:",o:["Inner retina","Choroid only","Corneal epithelium","Lens nucleus","Vitreous cortex"],a:0,e:"The central retinal artery supplies the inner retinal layers, and its occlusion causes sudden ischemic infarction of the inner retina.<br><br>The fovea appears red because it receives nutrition from underlying choroidal circulation.<br><br>Cornea, lens, and vitreous are avascular and not directly affected by CRAO.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diabetic retinopathy develops neovascularization elsewhere (NVE). This finding indicates:",o:["Non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy only","Proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Retinitis pigmentosa","Hypertensive crisis only"],a:1,e:"Neovascularization elsewhere or at the disc signifies proliferative diabetic retinopathy caused by retinal ischemia and VEGF release.<br><br>Untreated neovascularization may lead to vitreous hemorrhage and tractional retinal detachment. Identifying high-risk proliferative features that mandate prompt panretinal photocoagulation is a recurring viva theme.<br><br>Non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy lacks pathological new vessel formation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ischemic CRVO is most at risk for neovascular glaucoma within approximately:",o:["24 hours","1 week","3 months","2 years","10 years"],a:2,e:"Neovascular glaucoma classically develops around 90 days after ischemic CRVO, giving rise to the term \"90-day glaucoma.\"<br><br>Close follow-up during this period is mandatory.<br><br>Immediate onset within days is uncommon, while years-long delays are less typical.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"In hypertensive retinopathy, arteriovenous nicking occurs because:",o:["Vein compresses artery","Sclerosed artery compresses vein","Retina detaches at crossing","Choroid compresses vessels","Vitreous traction develops"],a:1,e:"Arteriolar sclerosis causes thickened retinal arteries to compress veins at crossing points, producing AV nicking.<br><br>This is a classic fundoscopic feature of chronic hypertension.<br><br>The vein does not compress the artery. Retinal detachment is unrelated to AV nicking.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular ischemic syndrome is most likely to have severe stenosis of the:",o:["Internal carotid artery","Vertebral artery","Central retinal vein","Ophthalmic vein","Posterior ciliary artery only"],a:0,e:"Ocular ischemic syndrome results from chronic hypoperfusion due to severe carotid artery stenosis, usually involving the internal carotid artery.<br><br>Patients may demonstrate venous dilation, mid-peripheral hemorrhages, and ocular pain.<br><br>Central retinal vein obstruction does not produce systemic carotid ischemic syndrome.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO still retains a small island of central vision. Which anatomical variation most likely explains this finding?",o:["Cilioretinal artery supply to macula","Retinal detachment","Optic disc drusen","Choroidal melanoma","Persistent hyaloid artery"],a:0,e:"Some individuals possess a cilioretinal artery arising from posterior ciliary circulation that may continue perfusing the macula despite CRAO.<br><br>This can preserve central vision partially.<br><br>Persistent hyaloid artery is a congenital vitreous anomaly unrelated to macular perfusion in CRAO.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular disorder most commonly presents with sudden painless unilateral profound visual loss?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Branch retinal vein occlusion","Hypertensive retinopathy","Background diabetic retinopathy","Macular degeneration"],a:0,e:"CRAO produces abrupt severe painless monocular blindness because of sudden interruption of retinal arterial perfusion.<br><br>The visual prognosis is generally poor unless circulation is restored rapidly.<br><br>BRVO and diabetic retinopathy usually produce less dramatic or more gradual visual decline.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 63-year-old hypertensive patient presents with sudden painless visual loss. Fundus examination reveals diffuse retinal hemorrhages, dilated tortuous veins, cotton wool spots, and marked disc edema. Relative afferent pupillary defect is present. Which subtype of CRVO is most likely?",o:["Non-ischemic CRVO","Ischemic CRVO","Impending CRVO","Papillophlebitis","Branch retinal vein occlusion"],a:1,e:"Ischemic CRVO is the severe form of CRVO characterized by profound visual loss, RAPD, extensive hemorrhages, and widespread retinal non-perfusion.<br><br>It carries high risk of neovascular glaucoma and poor visual prognosis. Fundus fluorescein angiography demonstrates large areas of capillary non-perfusion. The four-quadrant blood-and-thunder fundus is an instantly recognisable pattern in clinical assessments.<br><br>Papillophlebitis occurs in younger patients with relatively benign course. BRVO produces sectoral rather than diffuse retinal involvement.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branch retinal vein occlusion most commonly develops the occlusion in which quadrant?",o:["Inferonasal","Inferotemporal","Superonasal","Superotemporal","Macular"],a:3,e:"The superotemporal quadrant is the commonest location for BRVO because it contains numerous arteriovenous crossings vulnerable to venous compression by arteriosclerotic arteries.<br><br>Macular BRVO is less common. Nasal quadrants are less frequently affected clinically.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man develops sudden painless monocular blindness. Fundus examination reveals a pale retina with a cherry-red spot. Which emergency management step should be attempted immediately?",o:["Panretinal photocoagulation","Ocular massage","Vitrectomy","Retinal cryotherapy","Scleral buckle surgery"],a:1,e:"CRAO is an ophthalmic emergency. Ocular massage may help dislodge an embolus distally and potentially restore limited retinal perfusion.<br><br>Other measures include acetazolamide, anterior chamber paracentesis, and urgent stroke workup. Sudden painless monocular loss with a cherry-red spot is a stem pattern examiners reuse frequently.<br><br>Panretinal photocoagulation is used later for retinal ischemic neovascularization, not acute CRAO management.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is most strongly associated with branch retinal vein occlusion?",o:["Myopia","Hypertension","Retinitis pigmentosa","Hyperthyroidism","Keratoconus"],a:1,e:"Systemic hypertension is the most important risk factor for BRVO because arteriosclerotic thickened arteries compress adjacent veins at AV crossings.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus and hyperlipidemia are also important associations.<br><br>Keratoconus and retinitis pigmentosa are unrelated corneal and retinal degenerative conditions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO demonstrates segmentation of retinal blood columns during fundoscopy. This finding is termed:",o:["Box-carring","Roth spots","AV nicking","Hard exudation","Macular star"],a:0,e:"Box-carring refers to segmentation and sludging of retinal blood columns caused by severely reduced retinal arterial perfusion in CRAO.<br><br>This is a difficult but.<br><br>Roth spots are retinal hemorrhages with pale centers, while AV nicking is seen in hypertensive retinopathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of neovascularization in ischemic CRVO is retinal release of:",o:["Histamine","Acetylcholine","VEGF","Dopamine","Melanin"],a:2,e:"Retinal ischemia stimulates vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) production, leading to neovascularization of retina, iris, and angle.<br><br>Anti-VEGF injections are now standard therapy for many retinal vascular disorders.<br><br>Histamine and dopamine do not drive ischemic retinal neovascularization clinically.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ocular ischemic syndrome is most likely to complain of:",o:["Gradual visual loss with ocular ache","Sudden severe ocular pain after trauma","Congenital night blindness","Monocular diplopia only","Colored halos only"],a:0,e:"Ocular ischemic syndrome due to severe carotid artery stenosis commonly presents with gradual visual decline accompanied by dull ocular pain from chronic hypoperfusion.<br><br>Mid-peripheral hemorrhages and venous dilation are typical fundus findings.<br><br>Night blindness and monocular diplopia are unrelated symptom patterns.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe hypertensive retinopathy develops papilledema. This finding indicates:",o:["Grade I hypertensive retinopathy","Grade II hypertensive retinopathy","Grade III hypertensive retinopathy","Grade IV hypertensive retinopathy","Diabetic retinopathy only"],a:3,e:"Papilledema in hypertensive retinopathy signifies malignant hypertension and defines Grade IV disease.<br><br>It is associated with severe systemic vascular compromise and requires urgent management.<br><br>Grade III disease includes hemorrhages and exudates without papilledema.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular disorder most commonly produces RAPD?",o:["Ischemic CRVO","Mild BRVO","Background diabetic retinopathy","Hypertensive retinopathy","Drusen"],a:0,e:"Severe retinal ischemia in ischemic CRVO damages retinal ganglion cell function sufficiently to produce a relative afferent pupillary defect.<br><br>RAPD is an important clinical clue distinguishing ischemic from non-ischemic CRVO.<br><br>Mild BRVO and background diabetic retinopathy usually do not produce significant RAPD.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO still demonstrates normal choroidal flush on fluorescein angiography because the choroid is supplied mainly by:",o:["Central retinal artery","Posterior ciliary arteries","Lacrimal artery","Angular artery","Superior ophthalmic vein"],a:1,e:"The choroidal circulation arises predominantly from posterior ciliary arteries rather than the central retinal artery.<br><br>Therefore, choroidal perfusion may remain intact despite CRAO. This explains the classic cherry-red spot appearance.<br><br>The superior ophthalmic vein is venous drainage rather than arterial supply.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with CRVO develops iris neovascularization. Which term best describes this finding?",o:["Rubeosis iridis","Heterochromia iridis","Aniridia","Iridodialysis","Corectopia"],a:0,e:"Rubeosis iridis refers to pathological neovascularization of the iris secondary to severe retinal ischemia.<br><br>It is strongly associated with ischemic CRVO, proliferative diabetic retinopathy, and ocular ischemic syndrome. Early detection of rubeosis preceding neovascular glaucoma is an emphasised management checkpoint.<br><br>Iridodialysis refers to traumatic iris root separation rather than neovascularization.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation best quantifies macular edema in retinal vein occlusion?",o:["OCT","Gonioscopy","Retinoscopy","Keratometry","Pachymetry"],a:0,e:"Optical coherence tomography (OCT) provides high-resolution cross-sectional imaging and accurately measures retinal thickness and macular edema.<br><br>OCT is now central to monitoring anti-VEGF treatment response in retinal vascular disease.<br><br>Keratometry and pachymetry evaluate corneal structures rather than retinal edema.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal arterial emboli most likely has emboli originating from:",o:["Carotid artery plaques","Corneal vessels","Ciliary body","Retinal pigment epithelium","Vitreous base"],a:0,e:"Most retinal arterial emboli arise from atherosclerotic carotid plaques or cardiac sources and may precipitate CRAO or BRAO.<br><br>Carotid Doppler and cardiovascular evaluation are essential.<br><br>The vitreous base and retinal pigment epithelium do not generate arterial emboli.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branch retinal artery occlusion most typically presents with:",o:["Sectoral visual field defect","Bilateral blindness","Painful red eye","Severe photophobia","Corneal edema"],a:0,e:"BRAO produces localized retinal ischemia corresponding to the occluded arterial territory, causing sectoral field defects.<br><br>Central acuity may remain preserved if the macula is spared.<br><br>Painful red eye and corneal edema are unrelated anterior segment findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe ischemic CRVO is at highest risk for neovascular glaucoma if extensive retinal ischemia exceeds approximately:",o:["2 disc areas","5 disc areas","20 disc areas","10 disc areas","40 disc areas"],a:3,e:"More than 10 disc areas of capillary non-perfusion on fluorescein angiography strongly predicts ischemic CRVO and risk of neovascular complications.<br><br>Smaller ischemic areas carry significantly lower neovascular risk.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old diabetic patient presents with sudden painless severe visual loss. Fundus examination reveals diffuse retinal whitening but the foveal region remains relatively red. Why does the fovea retain its reddish appearance in CRAO?",o:["Presence of retinal pigment hypertrophy","Absence of inner retinal layers at fovea","Excessive vitreous transparency","Increased retinal arterial supply","Macular edema sparing"],a:1,e:"The fovea lacks thick inner retinal layers, allowing underlying intact choroidal circulation to remain visible despite surrounding retinal ischemia. This creates the classic cherry-red spot of CRAO.<br><br>The surrounding retina becomes pale because infarcted inner retinal layers turn opaque and edematous. Sudden severe loss from vitreous haemorrhage in a diabetic is a recurring high-stakes presentation.<br><br>Retinal arterial supply is actually interrupted in CRAO. Vitreous transparency does not account for selective foveal redness.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ischemic CRVO develops severe ocular pain, corneal edema, and markedly elevated intraocular pressure three months later. Which mechanism most likely explains this complication?",o:["Lens-induced pupillary block","Iris neovascularization obstructing angle","Retinal detachment","Vitreous syneresis","Choroidal rupture"],a:1,e:"Severe retinal ischemia induces VEGF-mediated neovascularization of iris and anterior chamber angle, leading to fibrovascular angle closure and neovascular glaucoma.<br><br>Lens block glaucoma and vitreous degeneration do not explain the ischemic neovascular process.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A hypertensive patient demonstrates flame-shaped retinal hemorrhages during fundoscopy. These hemorrhages are located primarily within the:",o:["Outer nuclear layer","Retinal nerve fiber layer","Choroid","Retinal pigment epithelium","Vitreous cortex"],a:1,e:"Flame-shaped hemorrhages spread along the orientation of retinal nerve fibers and therefore appear linear or flame-like clinically.<br><br>They are classically associated with hypertension, retinal vein occlusions, and papilledema.<br><br>Dot-blot hemorrhages occur deeper within the retina rather than in the nerve fiber layer.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with non-ischemic CRVO most commonly differs from ischemic CRVO by having:",o:["Worse visual prognosis","Extensive capillary non-perfusion","Better visual acuity at presentation","Severe RAPD","High risk of neovascular glaucoma"],a:2,e:"Non-ischemic CRVO usually presents with relatively preserved vision, minimal RAPD, and less retinal ischemia compared with ischemic CRVO.<br><br>Visual prognosis is significantly better, and neovascular complications are less frequent.<br><br>Extensive capillary non-perfusion and severe RAPD strongly suggest ischemic CRVO instead.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which systemic disease is most strongly associated with central retinal artery occlusion in elderly patients?",o:["Temporal arteritis","Asthma","Psoriasis","Hyperthyroidism","Ulcerative colitis"],a:0,e:"Giant cell (temporal) arteritis is a critical cause of arteritic CRAO in elderly patients and represents an ophthalmic emergency because the fellow eye is at high risk.<br><br>Symptoms may include scalp tenderness, jaw claudication, and elevated ESR. Immediate systemic corticosteroids are essential.<br><br>Psoriasis and asthma do not typically precipitate retinal arterial occlusion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with BRVO develops sudden worsening of vision months later. OCT demonstrates cystoid spaces in the macula. Which complication has developed?",o:["Macular edema","Retinal dialysis","Choroidal rupture","Papilledema","Retinitis pigmentosa"],a:0,e:"Macular edema is the commonest cause of delayed visual deterioration in BRVO and is readily identified on OCT as intraretinal cystic spaces.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy has become first-line treatment in many such patients.<br><br>Retinal dialysis and choroidal rupture are traumatic conditions unrelated to BRVO progression.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular disorder most commonly presents with \"venous tortuosity\" and \"disc edema\" together?",o:["Ischemic CRVO","CRAO","Dry ARMD","Retinal detachment","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"CRVO classically produces dilated tortuous veins accompanied by optic disc edema because venous outflow obstruction causes retinal congestion.<br><br>CRAO causes attenuated arteries rather than tortuous engorged veins.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe carotid stenosis demonstrates mid-peripheral retinal hemorrhages and narrowed retinal arteries. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinitis pigmentosa","Ocular ischemic syndrome","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Vitreomacular traction","Stargardt disease"],a:1,e:"Ocular ischemic syndrome occurs because of chronic carotid hypoperfusion and produces narrowed arteries, dilated veins, and mid-peripheral hemorrhages.<br><br>Patients often complain of dull ocular pain and gradual visual decline.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa causes bone-spicule pigmentation rather than vascular ischemic hemorrhages.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"In retinal vein occlusion, cotton wool spots indicate:",o:["Retinal detachment","Lipid deposition only","Choroidal rupture","Local retinal ischemia","Vitreous liquefaction"],a:3,e:"Cotton wool spots represent focal infarctions of the retinal nerve fiber layer secondary to ischemia and interrupted axoplasmic transport.<br><br>They are important markers of retinal hypoxia in vein occlusions and diabetic retinopathy.<br><br>Hard exudates represent lipid leakage, not infarction. Vitreous liquefaction is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy develops sudden dense vitreous hemorrhage. The source of bleeding is most likely:",o:["Retinal pigment epithelium","Fragile neovascular vessels","Choroidal melanoma","Ciliary body cyst","Posterior capsule rupture"],a:1,e:"New vessels formed in proliferative diabetic retinopathy are fragile and prone to bleeding into the vitreous cavity.<br><br>Repeated vitreous hemorrhage may eventually require pars plana vitrectomy. Acute dense vitreous haemorrhage obscuring the fundus is a classic indication-for-ultrasound scenario.<br><br>Retinal pigment epithelium and ciliary body cysts do not typically produce diabetic vitreous hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO is found to have a visible yellow refractile embolus at a retinal arterial bifurcation. This embolus is most likely composed of:",o:["Cholesterol","Calcium oxalate","Melanin","Hemosiderin","Copper"],a:0,e:"Cholesterol emboli (Hollenhorst plaques) originate most commonly from carotid atherosclerotic plaques and appear bright yellow and refractile.<br><br>Their identification mandates urgent systemic vascular evaluation.<br><br>Melanin and hemosiderin are unrelated to retinal arterial embolic disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most useful for identifying carotid artery stenosis in ocular ischemic syndrome?",o:["OCT","B-scan ultrasonography","Carotid Doppler ultrasound","Keratometry","Gonioscopy"],a:2,e:"Carotid Doppler ultrasound noninvasively evaluates carotid stenosis and is essential in suspected ocular ischemic syndrome or embolic retinal vascular disease.<br><br>OCT evaluates retina structurally but does not assess carotid circulation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hypertensive retinopathy demonstrates silver wiring of retinal arteries. This occurs because of:",o:["Retinal edema","Sclerotic thickening of arterial wall","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","Optic disc edema"],a:1,e:"Advanced arteriosclerosis causes increased light reflex from thickened arterial walls, eventually producing \"silver wiring.\"<br><br>Retinal edema and vitreous hemorrhage do not create metallic arterial light reflexes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRVO undergoes fluorescein angiography. Extensive capillary non-perfusion is demonstrated. Which complication is most feared?",o:["Cataract","Dry eye disease","Retinal drusen","Neovascular glaucoma","Corneal dystrophy"],a:3,e:"Large ischemic retinal areas release VEGF and strongly predispose to iris and angle neovascularization followed by neovascular glaucoma.<br><br>Dry eye disease and corneal dystrophy are unrelated anterior segment disorders.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branch retinal artery occlusion retains normal central vision. Which explanation is most likely?",o:["Macula spared from ischemic territory","Choroidal rupture prevented edema","Vitreous traction improved circulation","Optic disc swelling preserved acuity","Corneal edema compensated vision"],a:0,e:"In BRAO, central vision may remain normal if the occluded arterial branch does not supply the foveal region.<br><br>Patients instead develop sectoral visual field defects corresponding to the ischemic retinal territory.<br><br>Optic disc swelling and vitreous traction do not preserve macular function in arterial occlusion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 66-year-old hypertensive male presents with sudden painless profound visual loss in the right eye for 4 hours. Fundoscopy reveals diffuse retinal whitening with a cherry-red spot at the fovea and attenuated retinal arteries. Which is the most appropriate immediate management step?",o:["Intravitreal antibiotics","Panretinal photocoagulation","Ocular massage and IOP lowering","Vitrectomy","Corneal transplantation"],a:2,e:"This patient has classic central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO), an ophthalmic emergency causing sudden severe painless monocular visual loss. Immediate ocular massage and reduction of intraocular pressure may help dislodge the embolus distally and restore partial retinal perfusion before irreversible retinal infarction develops.<br><br>Additional measures may include acetazolamide, anterior chamber paracentesis, carbogen therapy, and urgent stroke/carotid workup because CRAO is strongly associated with systemic vascular disease. Visual prognosis rapidly worsens after several hours of ischemia. The profound painless loss with arteriolar attenuation is a pattern repeatedly used to test localisation.<br><br>Panretinal photocoagulation (B) is used for ischemic retinal neovascularization rather than acute CRAO. Vitrectomy (D) is reserved for vitreoretinal disorders like non-clearing vitreous hemorrhage. Corneal transplantation (E) has no role in retinal vascular occlusion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old diabetic woman presents with blurred vision. Fundoscopy shows diffuse retinal hemorrhages in all quadrants, dilated tortuous veins, cotton wool spots, and optic disc edema. RAPD is present. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Branch retinal vein occlusion","Hypertensive retinopathy","Ischemic central retinal vein occlusion","Central retinal artery occlusion","Papillitis"],a:2,e:"Ischemic CRVO presents with severe venous congestion producing the classic \"blood and thunder\" appearance: widespread hemorrhages, venous tortuosity, cotton wool spots, and disc edema. Presence of RAPD strongly suggests significant retinal ischemia.<br><br>Fundus fluorescein angiography demonstrates extensive capillary non-perfusion, while OCT helps assess associated macular edema. Recognising clinically significant macular oedema as the chief cause of central vision loss is a core teaching point.<br><br>BRVO (A) affects only a retinal sector rather than all quadrants. CRAO (D) produces retinal pallor with attenuated arteries instead of diffuse hemorrhagic congestion. Papillitis (E) causes disc swelling but not extensive retinal hemorrhages.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 61-year-old man complains of sudden painless blurring of vision in one eye. Examination reveals retinal hemorrhages confined to the superotemporal quadrant with venous dilation crossing an AV junction. What is the most likely underlying mechanism?",o:["Compression of vein by sclerosed artery","Choroidal ischemia","Retinal tear formation","Optic nerve infarction","Vitreous traction syndrome"],a:0,e:"Branch retinal vein occlusion usually occurs at arteriovenous crossing sites where a thickened arteriosclerotic retinal artery compresses the adjacent vein, producing turbulent flow and thrombosis. The superotemporal quadrant is the commonest site.<br><br>Hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hyperlipidemia are major systemic risk factors. Sectoral hemorrhages with venous tortuosity and macular edema are classic findings.<br><br>Choroidal ischemia (B) does not cause localized venous thrombosis patterns. Retinal tears (C) lead to retinal detachment rather than hemorrhagic venous congestion. Vitreous traction (E) is unrelated to BRVO pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ischemic CRVO returns three months later with severe ocular pain and redness. Examination reveals iris neovascularization and markedly elevated intraocular pressure. Which complication has developed?",o:["Phacomorphic glaucoma","Angle recession glaucoma","Neovascular glaucoma","Pigmentary glaucoma","Phacolytic glaucoma"],a:2,e:"Retinal ischemia in ischemic CRVO stimulates VEGF release, producing neovascularization of the iris and anterior chamber angle. Fibrovascular membrane formation eventually closes the angle and causes severe secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Prompt anti-VEGF therapy and panretinal photocoagulation are essential to reduce ischemic drive and preserve the eye. Prognosis becomes poor once uncontrolled neovascular glaucoma develops.<br><br>Phacomorphic and phacolytic glaucoma (A, E) are lens-induced glaucomas. Angle recession glaucoma follows ocular trauma rather than retinal ischemia. Pigmentary glaucoma occurs due to pigment dispersion syndrome.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 73-year-old woman develops transient episodes of monocular visual blackout lasting a few minutes each. Which diagnosis best describes this symptom?",o:["Nyctalopia","Metamorphopsia","Photopsia","Amaurosis fugax","Diplopia"],a:3,e:"Amaurosis fugax refers to transient monocular visual loss caused by temporary retinal ischemia, commonly from emboli arising from carotid atherosclerotic disease. It is considered a retinal transient ischemic attack.<br><br>This symptom is extremely high yield because it may precede permanent CRAO or cerebral stroke. Urgent carotid Doppler and cardiovascular evaluation are mandatory.<br><br>Nyctalopia (A) means night blindness and is classically associated with retinitis pigmentosa. Metamorphopsia (B) indicates distorted vision from macular pathology. Diplopia (E) suggests ocular misalignment rather than retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy develops sudden dense vitreous hemorrhage. Which structure is most likely responsible for the bleeding?",o:["Posterior ciliary artery","Fragile retinal neovascular vessels","Choroidal melanoma","Optic nerve drusen","Retinal pigment epithelium"],a:1,e:"Proliferative diabetic retinopathy produces abnormal fragile new vessels that easily rupture and bleed into the vitreous cavity. Recurrent hemorrhage may eventually cause tractional retinal detachment.<br><br>Management includes anti-VEGF injections, panretinal photocoagulation, and pars plana vitrectomy for persistent non-clearing hemorrhage. Tractional detachment complicating untreated PDR is a frequently examined surgical-referral trigger.<br><br>Posterior ciliary arteries (A) mainly supply the choroid. Optic disc drusen (D) may mimic disc edema but do not cause diabetic vitreous hemorrhage. Retinal pigment epithelium (E) is not the source of proliferative bleeding.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO is found to have a visible yellow refractile embolus at an arterial bifurcation during fundoscopy. What is this embolus most likely called?",o:["Roth spot","Hollenhorst plaque","Elschnig pearl","Drusen body","Hard exudate"],a:1,e:"Hollenhorst plaques are cholesterol emboli usually originating from carotid atherosclerotic plaques. They appear bright, refractile, and yellow at retinal arterial bifurcations.<br><br>Identification mandates urgent carotid and cardiovascular evaluation because patients are at high risk for stroke and future retinal arterial occlusion.<br><br>Roth spots (A) are hemorrhages with pale centers seen in infective endocarditis and leukemia. Elschnig pearls (C) occur in posterior capsular opacification after cataract surgery. Hard exudates (E) represent lipid leakage rather than emboli.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe hypertensive retinopathy demonstrates papilledema, cotton wool spots, flame hemorrhages, and macular star formation. This corresponds to which grade of hypertensive retinopathy?",o:["Grade I","Grade II","Grade III","Grade IV","Diabetic retinopathy"],a:3,e:"Grade IV hypertensive retinopathy represents malignant hypertension and is characterized by papilledema in addition to retinal hemorrhages, exudates, cotton wool spots, and vascular narrowing.<br><br>Grade III hypertensive retinopathy lacks papilledema. Grade I and II involve milder vascular narrowing and AV nicking without severe retinal ischemic signs.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with BRVO develops decreased central vision. OCT reveals cystic intraretinal spaces involving the fovea. Which complication is present?",o:["Macular edema","Retinal dialysis","Optic neuritis","Choroidal rupture","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"Macular edema is the commonest cause of visual impairment in branch retinal vein occlusion. Leakage from incompetent retinal vessels causes intraretinal cystic fluid accumulation detectable on OCT.<br><br>OCT monitoring and anti-VEGF therapy are central components of modern BRVO management.<br><br>Macular hole (E) produces full-thickness foveal defects rather than cystoid edema. Retinal dialysis (B) is a traumatic peripheral retinal tear unrelated to BRVO. Optic neuritis (C) affects the optic nerve rather than retinal vasculature.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CRAO retains surprisingly preserved central visual acuity despite extensive retinal ischemia. Which anatomical variation most likely explains this finding?",o:["Cilioretinal artery supplying macula","Persistent hyaloid artery","Posterior vitreous detachment","Retinal dialysis","Choroidal nevus"],a:0,e:"A cilioretinal artery originates from posterior ciliary circulation rather than the central retinal artery. If present, it may continue perfusing the macula even after CRAO, preserving central vision partially.<br><br>Recognition has prognostic significance during retinal vascular assessment.<br><br>Persistent hyaloid artery (B) is a congenital vitreous anomaly unrelated to macular perfusion. Posterior vitreous detachment (C) and retinal dialysis (D) are vitreoretinal disorders without protective arterial supply function.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 72-year-old smoker complains of gradual painless central visual loss and distortion of straight lines. Fundoscopy reveals drusen and retinal pigment epithelial changes at the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Branch retinal vein occlusion","Retinitis pigmentosa","Dry age-related macular degeneration","Retinal detachment"],a:3,e:"Dry age-related macular degeneration (ARMD) is characterized by drusen deposition and retinal pigment epithelial atrophy causing progressive central visual decline and metamorphopsia. Smoking is a major risk factor.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of difficulty reading and recognizing faces while peripheral vision remains relatively preserved. Amsler grid testing is useful for detecting metamorphopsia.<br><br>CRAO causes sudden severe visual loss rather than gradual central distortion. Retinitis pigmentosa primarily affects peripheral vision and night vision. Retinal detachment typically presents with flashes, floaters, and field defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly suggests wet (neovascular) ARMD rather than dry ARMD?",o:["Peripheral retinal degeneration","Vitreous hemorrhage only","Bone-spicule pigmentation","Choroidal neovascular membrane","Optic disc edema"],a:3,e:"Wet ARMD occurs when abnormal choroidal neovascularization develops beneath the retina, causing leakage, hemorrhage, and rapid central visual deterioration.<br><br>This form accounts for most severe visual loss associated with ARMD despite being less common than dry ARMD. Anti-VEGF therapy has revolutionized management.<br><br>Bone-spicule pigmentation is characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Optic disc edema is unrelated to macular degeneration pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with macular disease reports that straight lines appear bent and distorted. This symptom is termed:",o:["Diplopia","Nyctalopia","Metamorphopsia","Photophobia","Scotoma"],a:2,e:"Metamorphopsia refers to distortion of images, especially straight lines appearing wavy, due to disruption of macular architecture.<br><br>It is a classic symptom of macular disorders such as ARMD, macular edema, and epiretinal membrane. Amsler grid testing is highly useful for detecting this abnormality.<br><br>Nyctalopia indicates night blindness, while diplopia results from ocular misalignment rather than retinal distortion. Scotoma represents an area of visual field loss rather than image deformation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The hallmark ophthalmoscopic finding in dry ARMD is:",o:["Cotton wool spots","Drusen","Cherry-red spot","Flame hemorrhages","Retinal detachment"],a:1,e:"Drusen are yellow extracellular deposits beneath the retinal pigment epithelium and represent the hallmark feature of dry ARMD.<br><br>Large soft drusen are associated with increased risk of progression to advanced disease and neovascular ARMD.<br><br>Cotton wool spots indicate retinal ischemia. Cherry-red spot occurs in CRAO, while flame hemorrhages are classically associated with hypertension.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD most commonly develops severe visual loss because of:",o:["Peripheral retinal degeneration","Optic nerve atrophy","Vitreous liquefaction","Choroidal neovascular leakage and scarring","Corneal edema"],a:3,e:"In wet ARMD, fragile choroidal neovascular membranes leak fluid and blood beneath the macula, ultimately causing fibrotic disciform scarring and irreversible central visual loss.<br><br>Prompt anti-VEGF therapy is therefore essential to preserve vision. Early diagnosis using OCT and fluorescein angiography is.<br><br>Peripheral retinal degeneration and vitreous liquefaction do not explain central macular destruction characteristic of neovascular ARMD.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most useful for detecting subretinal fluid in wet ARMD?",o:["Gonioscopy","Schiotz tonometry","Keratometry","OCT","Retinoscopy"],a:3,e:"Optical coherence tomography (OCT) provides high-resolution cross-sectional imaging of retinal layers and is extremely sensitive for detecting intraretinal and subretinal fluid in wet ARMD.<br><br>OCT is now indispensable for diagnosis, treatment planning, and monitoring anti-VEGF response.<br><br>Keratometry evaluates corneal curvature, while gonioscopy examines the anterior chamber angle rather than macular pathology.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old diabetic patient develops gradual painless central visual blurring. Fundoscopy reveals circinate hard exudates around the fovea. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central serous chorioretinopathy","Diabetic macular edema","Retinitis pigmentosa","CRAO","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Diabetic macular edema results from breakdown of the blood-retinal barrier causing fluid and lipid leakage around the macula. Circinate hard exudates are characteristic.<br><br>OCT and fluorescein angiography help quantify edema and leakage. Differentiating dry from wet ARMD on the basis of metamorphopsia and fluid is a recurring decision point.<br><br>CRAO presents suddenly with retinal pallor rather than lipid exudation. Retinitis pigmentosa primarily affects peripheral retina and night vision.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient complains of a central dark spot in vision while peripheral vision remains normal. Which term best describes this defect?",o:["Hemianopia","Peripheral scotoma","Central scotoma","Tunnel vision","Diplopia"],a:2,e:"Macular diseases frequently produce central scotomas because the fovea is responsible for high-resolution central vision.<br><br>Patients complain of difficulty reading and facial recognition despite intact peripheral fields. This symptom is strongly associated with ARMD and other acquired macular disorders.<br><br>Tunnel vision is characteristic of advanced glaucoma or retinitis pigmentosa. Diplopia results from ocular misalignment rather than retinal pathology.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old man develops sudden central visual blurring after emotional stress. OCT demonstrates localized neurosensory retinal detachment at the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Wet ARMD","Central serous chorioretinopathy","CRAO","Macular hole","Retinal detachment"],a:1,e:"Central serous chorioretinopathy (CSCR) occurs due to leakage through the retinal pigment epithelium causing serous detachment of the neurosensory retina.<br><br>It classically affects young to middle-aged stressed males and may be associated with corticosteroid use. Metamorphopsia and micropsia are common symptoms. The young stressed male with acute central blur and serous detachment is a stem examiners favour.<br><br>Wet ARMD usually affects older patients with choroidal neovascularization. Macular holes produce full-thickness retinal defects rather than serous detachments.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which lifestyle factor most strongly increases risk for ARMD progression?",o:["Vegetarian diet","Smoking","Myopia","Hyperthyroidism","Keratoconus"],a:1,e:"Smoking is one of the strongest modifiable risk factors for ARMD because it promotes oxidative retinal damage and choroidal vascular compromise.<br><br>Myopia and keratoconus are unrelated refractive and corneal disorders rather than primary ARMD risk factors.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A full-thickness defect at the fovea is characteristic of:",o:["Macular hole","Dry ARMD","Papilledema","Retinal vein occlusion","Retinitis pigmentosa"],a:0,e:"Macular hole is a full-thickness foveal defect commonly caused by vitreomacular traction. Patients present with central visual distortion and reduced acuity.<br><br>OCT is diagnostic and pars plana vitrectomy with internal limiting membrane peeling is the standard surgical treatment.<br><br>Dry ARMD causes drusen and atrophy rather than full-thickness retinal defects. Papilledema affects the optic disc rather than the fovea.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which test is particularly useful for home monitoring of macular distortion in ARMD?",o:["Ishihara chart","Snellen chart","Hess chart","Amsler grid","Schirmer test"],a:3,e:"The Amsler grid helps detect metamorphopsia and early central visual distortion in macular disorders such as wet ARMD.<br><br>Patients are advised to monitor each eye separately because new distortion may indicate development of choroidal neovascularization requiring urgent treatment.<br><br>Ishihara charts assess color vision, while Schirmer testing evaluates tear secretion rather than macular function.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder is most strongly associated with corticosteroid use?",o:["Macular hole","Diabetic macular edema","Wet ARMD","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Retinal detachment"],a:3,e:"CSCR is strongly associated with corticosteroid exposure and stress-related endogenous cortisol excess.<br><br>Patients often present with sudden unilateral central blur, micropsia, and metamorphopsia. Most cases resolve spontaneously, though persistent cases may require laser or photodynamic therapy.<br><br>Macular holes and diabetic macular edema are not classically steroid-induced disorders. Retinal detachment involves peripheral retinal breaks rather than serous macular leakage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD receives repeated intravitreal injections. Which medication class is most commonly used?",o:["Beta blockers","Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Cycloplegics","Anti-VEGF agents","Antihistamines"],a:3,e:"Anti-VEGF drugs such as ranibizumab, aflibercept, and bevacizumab inhibit pathological choroidal neovascularization and reduce retinal fluid leakage in wet ARMD.<br><br>Cycloplegics and beta blockers do not suppress retinal neovascular membranes. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors are mainly used in glaucoma management.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ARMD retains peripheral vision despite severe central visual loss because the disease primarily affects the:",o:["Peripheral retina","Macula","Optic nerve","Choroid only","Vitreous base"],a:1,e:"The macula is responsible for central detailed vision, color perception, and reading ability. ARMD selectively damages this region while sparing peripheral retinal function.<br><br>Patients therefore maintain mobility and orientation despite inability to read or recognize faces clearly.<br><br>Optic nerve diseases typically produce broader field defects, while peripheral retinal degeneration affects side vision rather than central acuity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with CSCR most commonly demonstrates which angiographic pattern on fluorescein angiography?",o:["Smoke-stack leakage","Lacy choroidal network","Delayed arterial filling","Window defect only","Disc leakage"],a:0,e:"Fluorescein angiography in CSCR classically demonstrates smoke-stack or ink-blot leakage patterns from focal retinal pigment epithelial defects.<br><br>OCT additionally shows localized neurosensory retinal detachment at the macula.<br><br>Delayed arterial filling is associated with arterial occlusive disease, while disc leakage suggests optic nerve inflammation or papilledema.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most commonly affects elderly smokers?",o:["CSCR","Retinitis pigmentosa","Stargardt disease","Wet ARMD","Macular dystrophy"],a:3,e:"Wet ARMD predominantly affects elderly individuals and is strongly linked to smoking and advancing age. Choroidal neovascularization causes rapid central visual deterioration.<br><br>Prompt anti-VEGF therapy is essential because untreated disease may lead to irreversible disciform scarring.<br><br>Stargardt disease is hereditary and presents earlier in life. Retinitis pigmentosa primarily affects peripheral retina rather than the macula.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diabetic macular edema most likely loses vision because of:",o:["Peripheral retinal tears","Retinal thickening involving the fovea","Choroidal rupture","Vitreous degeneration","Optic nerve compression"],a:1,e:"Leakage from incompetent retinal capillaries causes retinal thickening and cystic edema at the macula, disrupting central visual function.<br><br>Clinically significant macular edema is a major cause of visual impairment in diabetes. OCT quantifies retinal thickness accurately.<br><br>Peripheral tears and vitreous degeneration do not primarily affect central macular acuity in diabetic disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with epiretinal membrane most commonly complains of:",o:["Sudden total blindness","Night blindness","Painful red eye","Distorted central vision","Peripheral flashes only"],a:3,e:"Epiretinal membranes produce wrinkling and traction of the macula, leading to metamorphopsia and blurred central vision.<br><br>OCT demonstrates the membrane and associated retinal distortion. Severe symptomatic cases may require vitrectomy with membrane peeling.<br><br>Night blindness is characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Painful red eye suggests anterior segment disease rather than macular traction pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder is most likely to resolve spontaneously without major intervention in many patients?",o:["Wet ARMD","Macular hole","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Diabetic macular edema","Disciform scar"],a:2,e:"Many cases of CSCR resolve spontaneously over weeks to months with recovery of visual acuity, particularly after stress reduction and discontinuation of corticosteroids.<br><br>However, recurrent or chronic cases may lead to retinal pigment epithelial damage and persistent visual symptoms.<br><br>Wet ARMD and diabetic macular edema generally require active treatment to prevent progressive visual loss. Macular holes rarely close spontaneously in adults.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 74-year-old smoker presents with sudden worsening of central vision distortion over two weeks. OCT demonstrates subretinal fluid and pigment epithelial detachment. Which subtype of ARMD is most likely present?",o:["Dry atrophic ARMD","Wet neovascular ARMD","Retinitis pigmentosa","Macular dystrophy","Hypertensive maculopathy"],a:1,e:"Wet ARMD occurs due to development of choroidal neovascular membranes beneath the macula, causing leakage, hemorrhage, and rapid central visual deterioration. OCT commonly reveals subretinal fluid and pigment epithelial detachment.<br><br>Patients often report rapid progression of metamorphopsia compared with the slower course of dry ARMD.<br><br>Dry ARMD usually progresses gradually without active subretinal leakage. Retinitis pigmentosa mainly affects peripheral retina and night vision rather than central neovascular macular disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with central serous chorioretinopathy most commonly complains that objects appear:",o:["Larger than normal","Distorted and smaller than normal","Completely absent","Double only","Excessively bright"],a:1,e:"CSCR commonly produces metamorphopsia and micropsia because neurosensory retinal detachment alters photoreceptor alignment at the macula.<br><br>Patients are usually young or middle-aged males with stress or corticosteroid exposure history. OCT demonstrates serous detachment of the neurosensory retina. Metamorphopsia with micropsia from a serous macular detachment is a classic descriptive clue.<br><br>Complete field loss is unusual in isolated CSCR. Diplopia generally indicates ocular misalignment rather than macular pathology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 69-year-old woman with ARMD suddenly notices a central dark patch in vision associated with metamorphopsia. Which investigation is most useful to confirm choroidal neovascularization?",o:["Gonioscopy","Schirmer test","Retinoscopy","Fundus fluorescein angiography","Pachymetry"],a:3,e:"FFA identifies leakage from choroidal neovascular membranes and remains an important investigation in wet ARMD assessment.<br><br>It helps localize and characterize neovascular activity, often alongside OCT imaging.<br><br>Gonioscopy examines the anterior chamber angle, while pachymetry measures corneal thickness rather than macular vascular pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing wet ARMD develops a fibrotic elevated lesion beneath the macula. This lesion is termed:",o:["Cotton wool spot","Roth spot","Macular star","Disciform scar","Retinal dialysis"],a:3,e:"Untreated or advanced wet ARMD may progress to fibrovascular disciform scar formation beneath the macula, producing irreversible central visual loss.<br><br>This represents the end stage of choroidal neovascularization and repeated hemorrhagic leakage. Early anti-VEGF therapy aims to prevent this outcome.<br><br>Cotton wool spots are ischemic retinal lesions, while retinal dialysis is a peripheral retinal tear associated with trauma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most classically demonstrates drusen between Bruch membrane and retinal pigment epithelium?",o:["Wet ARMD","Macular hole","CSCR","Dry ARMD","Epiretinal membrane"],a:3,e:"Drusen are extracellular deposits accumulating between Bruch membrane and retinal pigment epithelium and are characteristic of dry ARMD.<br><br>Large soft drusen increase the likelihood of progression to advanced atrophic or neovascular disease.<br><br>Macular holes involve full-thickness retinal defects, while epiretinal membranes occur on the retinal surface rather than beneath the RPE.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with epiretinal membrane develops progressive central distortion. Which pathological process best explains this condition?",o:["Choroidal ischemia","Fibrocellular proliferation over macula","Optic nerve infarction","Vitreous hemorrhage only","Corneal endothelial failure"],a:1,e:"Epiretinal membranes consist of fibrocellular tissue proliferating over the inner retinal surface, causing tangential traction and retinal wrinkling.<br><br>Patients experience metamorphopsia and blurred central vision. OCT clearly demonstrates the membrane and associated retinal distortion.<br><br>Optic nerve infarction and corneal endothelial failure do not produce characteristic macular traction changes. Vitreous hemorrhage alone does not create retinal wrinkling.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests macular rather than optic nerve disease?",o:["Peripheral field constriction","Total color blindness","RAPD","Central metamorphopsia","Altitudinal field defect"],a:3,e:"Metamorphopsia is highly suggestive of macular pathology because distortion arises from disruption of foveal photoreceptor alignment.<br><br>Macular disorders typically produce central distortion with relatively preserved peripheral fields.<br><br>RAPD and altitudinal field defects are more typical of optic nerve pathology than isolated macular disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diabetic macular edema undergoes OCT. Which OCT finding most likely explains reduced visual acuity?",o:["Peripheral retinal thinning","Increased central retinal thickness","Choroidal rupture","Optic nerve cupping","Vitreous syneresis"],a:1,e:"Fluid accumulation within the macula causes retinal thickening and cystoid changes that disrupt foveal architecture and reduce visual acuity.<br><br>OCT quantification of retinal thickness is central to monitoring diabetic macular edema treatment response. Anti-VEGF injections are frequently required.<br><br>Peripheral thinning and vitreous syneresis do not primarily affect central acuity in diabetic macular edema.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD receives intravitreal ranibizumab injections. The primary mechanism of this drug is inhibition of:",o:["Dopamine","Histamine","Acetylcholine","VEGF","Carbonic anhydrase"],a:3,e:"Ranibizumab inhibits vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), reducing pathological choroidal neovascularization and retinal leakage in wet ARMD.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy dramatically improved visual outcomes in neovascular macular disease.<br><br>Histamine and dopamine pathways are unrelated to choroidal neovascular membrane formation. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors are primarily glaucoma medications.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic CSCR is most at risk of developing:",o:["Retinal pigment epithelial atrophy","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Papilledema","Corneal edema","Retinal dialysis"],a:0,e:"Persistent or recurrent CSCR may damage the retinal pigment epithelium, causing permanent visual disturbances and reduced contrast sensitivity.<br><br>Although many acute cases resolve spontaneously, chronic disease may require laser or photodynamic therapy.<br><br>Acute angle closure glaucoma and retinal dialysis are unrelated disorders involving the anterior chamber angle and peripheral retina respectively.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with macular hole most commonly experiences which symptom initially?",o:["Peripheral flashes only","Central visual distortion","Severe ocular pain","Total blindness","Colored halos"],a:1,e:"Macular holes commonly begin with metamorphopsia and blurred central vision before progressing to more severe central visual loss.<br><br>Vitreomacular traction is the usual underlying mechanism. OCT is diagnostic and guides surgical management planning.<br><br>Peripheral flashes are more suggestive of posterior vitreous detachment or retinal tears. Severe pain and halos suggest acute glaucoma rather than macular pathology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most commonly affects middle-aged stressed men?",o:["Wet ARMD","Dry ARMD","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Diabetic macular edema","Retinal vein occlusion"],a:2,e:"CSCR classically affects young to middle-aged males and is strongly associated with stress, type-A personality traits, and corticosteroid exposure.<br><br>Patients usually present with sudden unilateral blurred central vision and metamorphopsia. Most cases improve spontaneously over time.<br><br>ARMD predominantly affects elderly individuals, while diabetic macular edema is associated with long-standing diabetes rather than stress-related mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced dry ARMD develops sharply demarcated areas of retinal pigment epithelial loss. Which process is occurring?",o:["Geographic atrophy","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","Choroidal rupture","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Geographic atrophy represents advanced dry ARMD characterized by sharply defined areas of retinal pigment epithelial and photoreceptor loss.<br><br>It causes progressive irreversible central visual decline and is a major advanced form of non-neovascular ARMD.<br><br>Retinal detachment and vitreous hemorrhage are distinct vitreoretinal pathologies unrelated to RPE atrophic degeneration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with epiretinal membrane undergoes vitrectomy because of severe symptoms. Which additional procedure is commonly performed?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Iridectomy","Corneal grafting","ILM peeling","Scleral buckle"],a:3,e:"Vitrectomy with internal limiting membrane (ILM) peeling helps relieve macular traction and reduce recurrence risk in symptomatic epiretinal membrane surgery.<br><br>OCT is essential preoperatively.<br><br>Trabeculectomy treats glaucoma, while scleral buckle is mainly used for rhegmatogenous retinal detachment rather than macular traction disorders.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most typical of bilateral advanced ARMD?",o:["Peripheral field loss","Difficulty recognizing faces","Sudden painful blindness","Diplopia","Colored halos around lights"],a:1,e:"Advanced macular degeneration severely affects central detailed vision required for facial recognition, reading, and fine visual tasks. Peripheral orientation vision is often preserved.<br><br>Patients may retain mobility despite severe reading impairment.<br><br>Peripheral field loss is more characteristic of glaucoma or retinitis pigmentosa. Diplopia and halos usually indicate extraocular muscle or corneal/glaucoma pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD develops subretinal hemorrhage. Which pathological process most directly caused this?",o:["Retinal arterial infarction","Corneal neovascularization","Vitreous traction only","Rupture of choroidal neovascular membrane","Optic disc edema"],a:3,e:"Fragile choroidal neovascular vessels in wet ARMD easily bleed beneath the retina, causing sudden worsening of central vision and metamorphopsia.<br><br>Subretinal hemorrhage is a major cause of rapid visual decline in neovascular ARMD and often requires urgent anti-VEGF treatment.<br><br>Retinal arterial infarction produces retinal pallor rather than subretinal bleeding. Corneal neovascularization is anatomically unrelated to macular hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder is most strongly associated with vitreomacular traction syndrome?",o:["Macular hole","Dry ARMD","CSCR","Retinitis pigmentosa","CRAO"],a:0,e:"Persistent vitreomacular traction can create a full-thickness foveal defect, resulting in macular hole formation.<br><br>OCT demonstrates tractional forces and staged macular hole progression. Vitrectomy with ILM peeling is often required for visual rehabilitation.<br><br>CSCR involves serous retinal detachment rather than tractional foveal rupture. CRAO is vascular ischemic disease unrelated to vitreomacular traction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ARMD reports preserved side vision but inability to read small print. Which retinal region is most likely affected?",o:["Peripheral retina","Optic disc only","Ora serrata","Macula and fovea","Choroid alone"],a:3,e:"The macula and especially the fovea are responsible for fine central visual acuity necessary for reading and detailed tasks.<br><br>ARMD selectively damages these structures while sparing peripheral retinal function.<br><br>Peripheral retinal disease mainly affects side vision and mobility rather than reading acuity. Optic disc pathology usually produces broader visual dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diabetic macular edema receives intravitreal bevacizumab. The main therapeutic effect is reduction of:",o:["Retinal traction","Vascular permeability","Lens opacity","Corneal edema","Optic nerve cupping"],a:1,e:"Anti-VEGF agents reduce vascular leakage and permeability from incompetent retinal capillaries, thereby decreasing macular edema and improving visual acuity.<br><br>They are now central to management of diabetic macular edema and wet ARMD. OCT monitoring guides retreatment intervals.<br><br>Lens opacity and optic nerve cupping are unrelated to VEGF-mediated retinal leakage mechanisms. Retinal traction usually requires surgical management instead.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most commonly demonstrates bilateral soft drusen in elderly patients?",o:["CSCR","Dry ARMD","Macular hole","Retinal detachment","CRAO"],a:1,e:"Soft drusen are characteristic of dry ARMD and commonly occur bilaterally in elderly individuals. They represent extracellular deposits beneath the retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Large confluent soft drusen strongly predict progression toward advanced geographic atrophy or neovascular ARMD.<br><br>CSCR typically affects younger patients with serous retinal detachment. CRAO causes acute retinal ischemia rather than chronic drusen accumulation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 71-year-old smoker presents with sudden worsening of central visual distortion over 1 week. Fundoscopy reveals subretinal hemorrhage and gray-green membrane beneath the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Dry ARMD","Macular hole","Central serous chorioretinopathy","Wet ARMD","Branch retinal vein occlusion"],a:3,e:"Wet age-related macular degeneration occurs due to choroidal neovascular membrane formation beneath the retina. Leakage and bleeding from these fragile vessels produce rapid central visual deterioration, metamorphopsia, and subretinal hemorrhage.<br><br>OCT and fluorescein angiography are key investigations for confirming active neovascularization and monitoring response.<br><br>Dry ARMD (A) usually causes slowly progressive atrophy without sudden hemorrhagic worsening. CSCR (C) causes serous detachment but usually affects younger patients and lacks subretinal neovascular membranes. Macular holes (B) produce full-thickness foveal defects rather than subretinal hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient complains that straight door frames appear bent and distorted. Which structure is most likely affected?",o:["Peripheral retina","Optic nerve head","Corneal endothelium","Macula","Ciliary body"],a:3,e:"Metamorphopsia results from disruption of normal photoreceptor alignment within the macula, especially the foveal region responsible for detailed central vision.<br><br>This symptom is classically associated with ARMD, epiretinal membrane, macular edema, and CSCR. Amsler grid testing is highly useful for detecting and monitoring such distortion clinically.<br><br>Optic nerve disease (B) more commonly causes RAPD, color desaturation, or field defects rather than image distortion. Peripheral retinal disease (A) typically affects side vision and flashes rather than central metamorphopsia. Corneal endothelial disorders (C) cause glare and edema instead of selective central distortion.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old diabetic patient presents with gradual painless blurring of central vision. OCT reveals cystoid spaces within the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["CRAO","Diabetic macular edema","Retinal detachment","Retinitis pigmentosa","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Diabetic macular edema develops because chronic hyperglycemia disrupts the blood-retinal barrier, causing vascular leakage and retinal thickening at the macula. OCT typically demonstrates cystoid intraretinal fluid accumulation.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy and focal/grid laser remain major management options. Macular oedema as the leading cause of vision loss in diabetic eyes is a heavily emphasised concept.<br><br>CRAO (A) presents with sudden severe visual loss and retinal pallor rather than chronic cystoid edema. Retinal detachment (C) causes flashes, floaters, and elevated retina. Papilledema (E) primarily affects the optic disc rather than causing isolated cystoid macular swelling.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most sensitive for detecting subtle subretinal fluid in macular disease?",o:["Gonioscopy","Retinoscopy","Schirmer test","OCT","Keratometry"],a:3,e:"Optical coherence tomography provides high-resolution cross-sectional imaging of retinal layers and is highly sensitive for identifying intraretinal and subretinal fluid.<br><br>It has become indispensable in wet ARMD, diabetic macular edema, epiretinal membrane, and CSCR evaluation. Serial OCT monitoring guides treatment decisions and prognosis.<br><br>Gonioscopy (A) examines the anterior chamber angle, not retinal layers. Retinoscopy (B) evaluates refractive error, while keratometry (E) measures corneal curvature rather than macular fluid.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic central serous chorioretinopathy is most at risk of developing which complication?",o:["Retinal pigment epithelial atrophy","Neovascular glaucoma","Corneal ulceration","Lens subluxation","Optic nerve glioma"],a:0,e:"Persistent or recurrent CSCR damages the retinal pigment epithelium and photoreceptors, eventually causing permanent visual disturbances and reduced contrast sensitivity.<br><br>Although many acute episodes resolve spontaneously, chronic disease may leave residual metamorphopsia and visual impairment. Progression of chronic CSCR to RPE decompensation and permanent loss is an important prognostic caution.<br><br>Neovascular glaucoma (B) is classically associated with ischemic CRVO or proliferative diabetic retinopathy rather than CSCR. Corneal ulceration (C) and lens subluxation (D) are unrelated anterior segment disorders.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD is treated with intravitreal ranibizumab. What is the principal therapeutic target of this drug?",o:["Histamine receptors","Carbonic anhydrase","VEGF","Dopamine receptors","Acetylcholine release"],a:2,e:"Ranibizumab inhibits vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), thereby suppressing choroidal neovascularization and reducing retinal vascular leakage.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy revolutionized management of neovascular ARMD and is among the most. Visual stabilization is now achievable in many patients.<br><br>Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (B) are mainly glaucoma medications. Histamine and dopamine pathways (A, D) are unrelated to choroidal neovascular membrane formation. Acetylcholine release (E) has no role in ARMD pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old woman with ARMD complains she cannot recognize faces but can still walk around independently. This occurs because ARMD primarily affects:",o:["Peripheral retina","Macular central vision","Optic chiasm","Entire visual pathway","Corneal transparency"],a:1,e:"The macula is responsible for detailed central visual tasks including reading and facial recognition. ARMD selectively damages this area while sparing most peripheral visual fields.<br><br>Patients therefore maintain mobility and orientation despite severe impairment of fine visual function.<br><br>Peripheral retinal disease (A) causes side vision loss and mobility problems rather than isolated reading difficulty. Optic chiasmal lesions (C) typically produce bitemporal field defects rather than selective central impairment. Corneal pathology (E) affects overall clarity rather than central specificity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with epiretinal membrane most commonly presents with:",o:["Sudden painful blindness","Colored halos","Peripheral visual field loss","Central visual distortion","Complete night blindness"],a:3,e:"Epiretinal membranes create tangential traction over the macula, causing retinal wrinkling and photoreceptor distortion that produce metamorphopsia and blurred central vision.<br><br>OCT clearly demonstrates the membrane and retinal traction. Severe symptomatic cases may require vitrectomy with membrane peeling.<br><br>Peripheral field loss (C) is more typical of glaucoma or retinitis pigmentosa. Colored halos (B) suggest corneal edema or acute glaucoma. Night blindness (E) is characteristic of rod dysfunction such as retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 57-year-old stressed businessman develops sudden unilateral blurred central vision. OCT reveals localized serous detachment of the neurosensory retina. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Wet ARMD","CRAO","Macular hole","CSCR","BRVO"],a:3,e:"Central serous chorioretinopathy results from leakage through retinal pigment epithelial defects causing serous detachment of the neurosensory retina. Stress and corticosteroid exposure are classic associations.<br><br>Patients commonly report micropsia, metamorphopsia, and central blur. Most cases resolve spontaneously, though recurrent disease may produce chronic retinal pigment epithelial damage.<br><br>Wet ARMD (A) usually occurs in elderly patients with choroidal neovascularization and hemorrhage. CRAO (B) presents with sudden severe retinal ischemia rather than serous detachment. BRVO (E) causes sectoral retinal hemorrhages and venous tortuosity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most commonly demonstrates smoke-stack leakage on fluorescein angiography?",o:["Dry ARMD","Diabetic macular edema","Retinitis pigmentosa","Macular hole","CSCR"],a:4,e:"Fluorescein angiography in CSCR classically demonstrates smoke-stack or ink-blot leakage patterns arising from focal retinal pigment epithelial defects.<br><br>OCT additionally confirms serous neurosensory retinal detachment.<br><br>Dry ARMD (A) primarily demonstrates drusen and atrophy rather than focal smoke-stack leakage. Macular holes (D) produce full-thickness foveal defects rather than angiographic dye plume patterns. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) causes peripheral retinal degeneration and bone-spicule pigmentation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with wet ARMD suddenly develops a dense central scotoma due to submacular hemorrhage. Which pathological structure most likely bled?",o:["Retinal artery","Optic disc capillaries","Central retinal vein","Choroidal neovascular membrane","Corneal vessels"],a:3,e:"Fragile neovascular vessels beneath the retina in wet ARMD easily rupture, producing subretinal hemorrhage and sudden deterioration of central vision.<br><br>This is a major cause of rapid irreversible visual decline if treatment is delayed. Anti-VEGF therapy aims to suppress these abnormal vessels.<br><br>Retinal arterial occlusion (A) causes retinal pallor rather than hemorrhage. Corneal vessels (E) are anatomically unrelated to macular bleeding. Optic disc capillaries (B) do not create isolated submacular hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder is most strongly associated with vitreomacular traction?",o:["Macular hole","Dry ARMD","Hypertensive retinopathy","CRAO","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Persistent vitreomacular traction can produce progressive foveal dehiscence culminating in a full-thickness macular hole.<br><br>Patients experience central blur and metamorphopsia. OCT is diagnostic and vitrectomy with internal limiting membrane peeling is standard surgical treatment.<br><br>CRAO (D) is a vascular ischemic emergency rather than a tractional disorder. Papilledema (E) involves optic disc swelling, while hypertensive retinopathy (C) causes vascular retinal changes rather than foveal traction.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced dry ARMD develops sharply demarcated regions of retinal pigment epithelial loss. What is this called?",o:["Disciform scar","Geographic atrophy","Macular edema","Retinoschisis","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Geographic atrophy represents advanced non-neovascular ARMD with progressive retinal pigment epithelial and photoreceptor degeneration.<br><br>It produces irreversible central visual decline and enlarging central scotomas.<br><br>Disciform scars (A) occur in wet ARMD due to neovascular fibrosis rather than pure atrophy. Macular edema (C) involves fluid accumulation instead of tissue loss. Papilledema (E) affects the optic nerve head rather than macular RPE.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests bilateral advanced macular disease?",o:["Night blindness","Peripheral flashes only","Painful red eye","Difficulty reading and facial recognition","Severe photophobia"],a:3,e:"Macular disorders impair detailed central visual tasks such as reading and recognizing faces because the fovea mediates highest visual acuity.<br><br>Patients may still navigate independently due to preserved peripheral fields.<br><br>Night blindness (A) is more characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Painful red eye (C) suggests anterior segment inflammation or glaucoma rather than isolated macular disease. Peripheral flashes (B) commonly occur with vitreoretinal traction or retinal tears.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with clinically significant macular edema most likely loses vision because of:",o:["Optic nerve infarction","Retinal thickening involving the fovea","Peripheral retinal tears","Corneal endothelial failure","Choroidal rupture"],a:1,e:"Fluid leakage from incompetent retinal capillaries causes retinal thickening and cystoid edema at the fovea, directly impairing central visual acuity.<br><br>OCT is essential for quantifying edema severity and monitoring anti-VEGF response. Clinically significant macular edema is among the leading causes of diabetic visual loss worldwide. Focal or grid laser versus anti-VEGF selection in CSME is a recurring management discussion.<br><br>Optic nerve infarction (A) causes optic neuropathy rather than cystoid macular swelling. Peripheral retinal tears (C) may predispose to retinal detachment but do not primarily produce diabetic central edema. Corneal endothelial failure (D) causes diffuse corneal edema instead of selective foveal dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder most commonly resolves spontaneously in many patients?",o:["Wet ARMD","Macular hole","CSCR","Geographic atrophy","Epiretinal membrane"],a:2,e:"Many acute episodes of CSCR resolve spontaneously over weeks to months with reabsorption of subretinal fluid and improvement of visual acuity.<br><br>Stress reduction and discontinuation of corticosteroids are important management steps. Persistent or recurrent disease may still cause permanent retinal pigment epithelial damage.<br><br>Wet ARMD (A) usually progresses without treatment and requires anti-VEGF injections. Macular holes (B) often need surgery for anatomical closure. Geographic atrophy (D) is irreversible degenerative disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with macular hole undergoes pars plana vitrectomy. Which additional procedure is commonly combined with surgery?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Internal limiting membrane peeling","Penetrating keratoplasty","Iridectomy","Scleral buckle only"],a:1,e:"Internal limiting membrane peeling helps relieve tangential traction and increases the likelihood of successful macular hole closure during vitrectomy.<br><br>Gas tamponade is also commonly used postoperatively.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (A) is a glaucoma surgery, while penetrating keratoplasty (C) is used for corneal disease. Scleral buckle (E) mainly treats rhegmatogenous retinal detachment rather than isolated macular holes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which acquired macular disorder is most strongly associated with elderly smokers and drusen formation?",o:["CSCR","Macular dystrophy","Retinitis pigmentosa","Wet ARMD","CRAO"],a:3,e:"Wet ARMD commonly develops in elderly patients with preexisting drusen and retinal pigment epithelial abnormalities. Smoking significantly increases progression risk.<br><br>The disease becomes vision-threatening once choroidal neovascularization develops. Anti-VEGF therapy is therefore crucial for preserving central acuity.<br><br>CSCR (A) usually affects younger stressed individuals. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) is hereditary and primarily affects peripheral retina and night vision. CRAO (E) is an acute vascular occlusive emergency rather than chronic degenerative maculopathy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with epiretinal membrane undergoes OCT. Which OCT feature is most characteristic?",o:["Full-thickness retinal defect","Surface retinal wrinkling with traction","Diffuse choroidal excavation","Retinal arterial non-perfusion","Optic disc cupping"],a:1,e:"Epiretinal membranes appear on OCT as hyperreflective membranes overlying the retina causing wrinkling, distortion, and traction of macular architecture.<br><br>These changes correlate clinically with metamorphopsia and blurred central vision. Surgical peeling may improve symptoms in severe cases.<br><br>Full-thickness retinal defects (A) are characteristic of macular holes. Retinal arterial non-perfusion (D) is seen in ischemic vascular disease rather than surface traction pathology. Optic disc cupping (E) indicates glaucomatous optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe bilateral ARMD asks why side vision remains intact despite inability to read. Which anatomical explanation is most accurate?",o:["Peripheral retina is relatively spared","Optic chiasm compensates for macular loss","Lens enlarges peripheral images","Choroid bypasses macular degeneration","Vitreous supports central acuity"],a:0,e:"ARMD selectively damages the macula while leaving most peripheral retinal function intact. Therefore, patients retain orientation and mobility despite severe impairment of central detailed vision.<br><br>The optic chiasm (B) does not compensate for retinal degeneration. Lens optics (C) do not selectively preserve peripheral retinal function. Vitreous support (E) has no role in maintaining peripheral visual fields.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 12-year-old boy presents with mild blurring of central vision. Fundus examination reveals a round yellow \"egg-yolk\" lesion at the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Stargardt disease","Wet ARMD","Retinitis pigmentosa","Best vitelliform macular dystrophy","CSCR"],a:3,e:"Best vitelliform macular dystrophy (Best disease) is an inherited macular dystrophy characterized by yellow vitelliform (\"egg-yolk\") lesions at the macula due to lipofuscin accumulation beneath the retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>It usually presents in childhood and follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern related to mutations in the BEST1 gene. Central vision may initially remain relatively preserved despite striking fundus appearance.<br><br>Stargardt disease (A) causes beaten-bronze macular atrophy with pisciform flecks rather than classic egg-yolk lesions. Wet ARMD (B) affects elderly patients with choroidal neovascularization. CSCR (E) causes serous detachment instead of lipofuscin vitelliform deposits.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Best disease is most commonly inherited in which pattern?",o:["Autosomal recessive","X-linked recessive","Sporadic only","Mitochondrial inheritance","Autosomal dominant"],a:4,e:"Best vitelliform macular dystrophy classically follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern with variable penetrance and expression.<br><br>Mutations usually involve the BEST1 gene encoding bestrophin-1 protein within the retinal pigment epithelium. Family history may be positive across multiple generations. Autosomal recessive inheritance (A) is characteristic of some other inherited retinal dystrophies. X-linked inheritance (B) is not the classic transmission pattern of Best disease. Sporadic occurrence alone (C) would not explain strong familial clustering.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is classically abnormal in Best vitelliform macular dystrophy despite relatively normal ERG findings?",o:["Visual evoked potential","Keratometry","Pachymetry","Electro-oculography","Fluorescein staining"],a:3,e:"Electro-oculography (EOG) is characteristically abnormal in Best disease because of retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction. The Arden ratio is typically markedly reduced.<br><br>Importantly, the electroretinogram (ERG) often remains normal because generalized retinal photoreceptor function is relatively preserved initially.<br><br>Visual evoked potentials (A) are not the hallmark diagnostic test. Pachymetry (C) and keratometry (B) evaluate corneal structures rather than retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction. Fluorescein staining (E) assesses corneal epithelial defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease most commonly develops loss of which type of vision first?",o:["Peripheral vision","Night vision","Central vision","Complete blindness","Binocular vision only"],a:2,e:"Best disease primarily affects the macula and therefore impairs central detailed vision responsible for reading and facial recognition. Peripheral vision is usually preserved.<br><br>Patients may initially complain of mild blurred central vision or metamorphopsia despite dramatic fundus appearance. Vision loss progression varies considerably among individuals. Night blindness (B) is more typical of rod dystrophies such as retinitis pigmentosa. Peripheral visual loss (A) is not the dominant early manifestation of Best disease. Complete blindness (D) is uncommon. Central vision loss with a preserved peripheral field in a vitelliform dystrophy is a classic pairing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The yellow vitelliform lesion in Best disease mainly represents accumulation of:",o:["Hemosiderin","Lipofuscin","Melanin","Calcium","Cholesterol crystals"],a:1,e:"The classic yellow \"egg-yolk\" lesion in Best disease is produced by abnormal accumulation of lipofuscin beneath the retinal pigment epithelium within the macular region.<br><br>Lipofuscin accumulation eventually damages retinal pigment epithelial cells and photoreceptors, contributing to progressive central visual dysfunction. The lipofuscin basis of the egg-yolk lesion is a favourite basic-science correlate.<br><br>Melanin (C) is a normal retinal pigment component but does not form vitelliform lesions. Cholesterol crystals (E) are associated with Hollenhorst plaques rather than inherited macular dystrophy. Hemosiderin (A) results from hemorrhage breakdown.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A teenager presents with bilateral vitelliform lesions at the macula but preserved peripheral visual fields. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinitis pigmentosa","Best disease","CRAO","Retinal detachment","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Best disease selectively involves the macula while sparing most peripheral retinal function, allowing peripheral fields to remain intact.<br><br>The disease typically presents in childhood or adolescence with bilateral vitelliform lesions and variable reduction of central visual acuity.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (A) characteristically causes peripheral field constriction and night blindness. CRAO (C) presents acutely with retinal pallor and profound visual loss rather than chronic bilateral vitelliform lesions. Papilledema (E) affects the optic disc, not the macula.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which gene mutation is most classically associated with Best vitelliform macular dystrophy?",o:["RB1","PAX6","ABCA4","BEST1","MYOC"],a:3,e:"Best disease is most commonly associated with mutations in the BEST1 gene encoding bestrophin-1 protein in the retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Defective bestrophin function leads to retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction and lipofuscin accumulation at the macula. ABCA4 mutations (C) are classically associated with Stargardt disease. RB1 mutations (A) occur in retinoblastoma. MYOC (E) is associated with juvenile open-angle glaucoma rather than macular dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which stage of Best disease classically demonstrates fragmentation of the egg-yolk lesion resembling scrambled egg appearance?",o:["Vitelliform stage","Atrophic stage","Vitelliruptive stage","Pseudohypopyon stage","Fibrotic stage"],a:2,e:"The vitelliruptive stage occurs when the vitelliform material breaks apart, producing the classic \"scrambled egg\" appearance at the macula.<br><br>This represents progression of lipofuscin degeneration and retinal pigment epithelial disruption. Visual acuity may begin declining more significantly during this phase. The vitelliruptive pseudohypopyon stage is a classic staged-progression question.<br><br>The vitelliform stage (A) contains an intact egg-yolk lesion. The atrophic stage (B) demonstrates retinal pigment epithelial degeneration rather than fragmented yellow material. Pseudohypopyon stage (D) involves layering of vitelliform contents rather than scrambled fragmentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease develops sudden worsening of central vision due to choroidal neovascularization. Which treatment is now commonly used?",o:["Cycloplegics","Anti-VEGF injections","Trabeculectomy","Oral steroids only","Corneal grafting"],a:1,e:"Choroidal neovascularization is a serious complication of advanced Best disease and may produce sudden visual decline from leakage or hemorrhage.<br><br>Intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy is currently the preferred treatment for neovascular complications and may significantly improve prognosis. Sudden vitelliform-stage deterioration from rupture is an instantly recognisable clinical shift.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (C) treats glaucoma, not macular neovascularization. Cycloplegics (A) and corneal grafting (E) have no primary role in managing neovascular Best disease. Oral steroids (D) are not standard treatment for CNV.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding ERG in Best disease is most accurate?",o:["ERG is universally absent","ERG is pathognomonic","ERG demonstrates rod loss only","ERG is usually normal","ERG shows optic nerve dysfunction"],a:3,e:"Despite significant retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction, generalized retinal photoreceptor activity measured by ERG is often preserved in Best disease.<br><br>Therefore, EOG is much more diagnostically valuable than ERG in this condition.<br><br>ERG absence (A) is not characteristic of Best disease. Rod-selective dysfunction (C) is more typical of retinitis pigmentosa. Optic nerve dysfunction (E) is not what ERG measures.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease most likely presents at which age group?",o:["Neonatal period only","Childhood or adolescence","Late elderly age only","Immediately after trauma","Only after cataract surgery"],a:1,e:"Best disease commonly presents during childhood or adolescence, although severity and progression vary greatly among affected individuals.<br><br>Fundus lesions may appear before significant visual symptoms develop. Screening family members is important because of autosomal dominant inheritance. Childhood presentation with a normal ERG but abnormal EOG is a defining examined feature.<br><br>Late elderly onset alone (C) is more suggestive of ARMD. Trauma (D) and cataract surgery (E) do not cause inherited vitelliform dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most characteristic of progressive Best disease?",o:["Metamorphopsia","Severe ocular pain","Colored halos","Peripheral flashes only","Complete night blindness"],a:0,e:"As macular architecture becomes disrupted in Best disease, patients frequently develop metamorphopsia and central visual distortion.<br><br>Amsler grid testing may help monitor progression and detect complications such as choroidal neovascularization. Colored halos (C) are more typical of corneal edema or glaucoma. Peripheral flashes (D) suggest vitreoretinal traction or retinal tears. Severe night blindness (E) is more characteristic of rod dystrophies like retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal layer is primarily dysfunctional in Best disease?",o:["Nerve fiber layer","Retinal pigment epithelium","Ganglion cell layer","Choroidal stroma only","Vitreous cortex"],a:1,e:"Best disease fundamentally represents retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction caused by abnormalities in bestrophin protein.<br><br>This dysfunction leads to impaired ion transport and accumulation of lipofuscin beneath the macula.<br><br>Ganglion cell layer disease (C) is more relevant to optic neuropathies or glaucoma. Vitreous cortex abnormalities (E) occur in vitreoretinal interface disorders rather than inherited vitelliform dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature helps differentiate Best disease from retinitis pigmentosa?",o:["Progressive visual loss","Genetic inheritance","Bilateral retinal involvement","Peripheral visual fields usually preserved","Retinal degeneration"],a:3,e:"Best disease mainly affects the macula and therefore preserves peripheral retinal function and side vision for long periods.<br><br>In contrast, retinitis pigmentosa characteristically causes progressive peripheral field constriction and night blindness due to rod degeneration.<br><br>Both diseases may be bilateral (C), inherited (B), and degenerative (E), so these features do not reliably distinguish them. General progressive visual loss (A) occurs in both disorders.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease develops retinal pigment epithelial atrophy after years of disease progression. Which visual defect is most likely?",o:["Central scotoma","Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Altitudinal defect","Total peripheral blindness"],a:0,e:"Progressive macular degeneration and retinal pigment epithelial atrophy in Best disease impair foveal function, producing central scotomas.<br><br>Patients experience difficulty reading and recognizing faces while maintaining peripheral orientation vision. Bitemporal hemianopia (B) suggests optic chiasmal lesions. Homonymous hemianopia (C) results from retrochiasmal neurological disease. Peripheral blindness (E) is more typical of advanced retinitis pigmentosa. End-stage RPE atrophy with central scarring is a recurring late-complication theme.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation best demonstrates structural macular changes in Best disease?",o:["OCT","Schirmer test","Gonioscopy","Keratometry","Tonography"],a:0,e:"Optical coherence tomography provides detailed cross-sectional visualization of vitelliform deposits, retinal layers, and associated fluid or atrophy in Best disease.<br><br>OCT is especially useful for monitoring progression and detecting complications such as choroidal neovascularization. Gonioscopy (C) evaluates the anterior chamber angle rather than macular structure. Schirmer testing (B) assesses tear production, while keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which fundoscopic appearance is most classically associated with the vitelliform stage of Best disease?",o:["Bone-spicule pigmentation","Egg-yolk lesion","Cherry-red spot","Macular star","Flame hemorrhages"],a:1,e:"The vitelliform stage demonstrates a sharply defined yellow submacular lesion resembling egg yolk due to lipofuscin accumulation.<br><br>This appearance is highly characteristic and. Visual acuity may remain surprisingly good at this stage. The egg-yolk macular appearance is among the most reproduced fundus images in assessments.<br><br>Bone-spicule pigmentation (A) is characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Cherry-red spot (C) occurs in CRAO. Flame hemorrhages (E) are associated with retinal vascular disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual function is usually preserved until relatively late in Best disease?",o:["Central acuity","Reading ability","Color vision","Peripheral vision","Contrast sensitivity"],a:3,e:"Because Best disease selectively affects the macula, peripheral retinal function generally remains intact until late stages.<br><br>Patients therefore often retain mobility despite progressive central visual dysfunction. Central acuity (A), reading ability (B), and contrast sensitivity (E) are commonly affected earlier due to macular involvement. Color vision (C) may also become impaired with central photoreceptor degeneration.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is the most important differential diagnosis of Best disease in elderly patients?",o:["Wet ARMD","Keratoconus","Acute glaucoma","Papilledema","Corneal ulcer"],a:0,e:"Adult vitelliform lesions and advanced Best disease may resemble wet age-related macular degeneration because both can produce central visual loss and subretinal changes.<br><br>Differentiation requires careful history, age correlation, imaging, and electrophysiology. Separating Best disease from adult vitelliform dystrophy is a classic differential pairing.<br><br>Keratoconus (B) is a corneal ectasia unrelated to macular dystrophy. Papilledema (D) affects the optic nerve head rather than causing vitelliform lesions. Corneal ulceration (E) produces painful anterior segment inflammation instead of inherited macular pathology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with Best disease has relatively good visual acuity despite striking fundus lesions. Which explanation is most accurate?",o:["Peripheral retina compensates completely","Choroidal circulation replaces retinal function","Optic nerve bypasses the lesion","Early disease may spare photoreceptor function significantly","Cornea increases image magnification"],a:3,e:"In early Best disease, dramatic vitelliform lesions may coexist with relatively preserved photoreceptor function and surprisingly good visual acuity.<br><br>Visual decline often occurs gradually as retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction and photoreceptor degeneration progress.<br><br>Peripheral retinal compensation (A) cannot fully preserve detailed central acuity. The optic nerve (C) does not bypass retinal pathology. Corneal magnification (E) has no role in maintaining macular function.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 14-year-old girl is found to have bilateral yellow macular lesions during routine examination. Visual acuity is nearly normal. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Stargardt disease","Retinitis pigmentosa","Wet ARMD","Best vitelliform macular dystrophy","CRAO"],a:3,e:"Best vitelliform macular dystrophy commonly presents in childhood or adolescence with bilateral yellow \"egg-yolk\" macular lesions. Vision may initially remain relatively preserved despite obvious fundus abnormalities.<br><br>The disease follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and results from retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction due to BEST1 mutation.<br><br>Wet ARMD (C) usually affects elderly individuals and is associated with choroidal neovascularization. Retinitis pigmentosa (B) primarily causes peripheral field loss and night blindness rather than isolated vitelliform macular lesions. CRAO (E) presents acutely with severe retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which electrophysiological investigation is classically reduced in Best disease?",o:["ERG b-wave amplitude","Pattern VEP latency","Arden ratio on EOG","Flash VEP only","Oscillatory potentials"],a:2,e:"Electro-oculography demonstrates a reduced Arden ratio because Best disease primarily involves retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction.<br><br>Importantly, ERG is usually normal because generalized retinal photoreceptor activity may remain preserved in early disease. The selectively reduced EOG with a normal ERG is the single most examined electrophysiology fact here.<br><br>ERG abnormalities (A) are more prominent in generalized retinal dystrophies like retinitis pigmentosa. VEP abnormalities (B, D) mainly reflect optic pathway dysfunction rather than primary retinal pigment epithelial disease. Oscillatory potentials (E) are commonly discussed in diabetic retinopathy rather than Best disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which inheritance pattern is most strongly associated with Best vitelliform macular dystrophy?",o:["X-linked dominant","Autosomal recessive","Sporadic mutation only","Mitochondrial inheritance","Autosomal dominant"],a:4,e:"Best disease classically demonstrates autosomal dominant inheritance with variable penetrance and expression among family members.<br><br>Family screening is therefore important because asymptomatic relatives may demonstrate characteristic EOG abnormalities or subtle fundus changes.<br><br>Autosomal recessive inheritance (B) is more typical of some retinal dystrophies such as certain forms of Stargardt disease. Mitochondrial inheritance (D) characterizes disorders like Leber hereditary optic neuropathy rather than Best disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which fundoscopic description best matches the vitelliruptive stage of Best disease?",o:["Bone-spicule pigmentation","Geographic atrophy only","Cherry-red spot","Scrambled egg appearance","Disciform scar"],a:3,e:"The vitelliruptive stage occurs when vitelliform material fragments irregularly, producing the characteristic \"scrambled egg\" appearance at the macula.<br><br>This stage represents progressive degeneration of lipofuscin material and retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction. Visual acuity may begin deteriorating more noticeably during this phase.<br><br>Bone-spicule pigmentation (A) is typical of retinitis pigmentosa. Cherry-red spot (C) occurs in CRAO. Geographic atrophy (B) represents a later degenerative stage rather than fragmented vitelliform material. Disciform scars (E) are more characteristic of advanced wet ARMD.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease most commonly complains initially of:",o:["Severe ocular pain","Peripheral field constriction","Central visual distortion","Sudden total blindness","Colored halos around lights"],a:2,e:"Because Best disease selectively affects the macula, patients commonly develop blurred central vision and metamorphopsia while peripheral vision remains relatively preserved.<br><br>Symptoms may initially be mild despite significant fundus lesions. Amsler grid testing can help identify subtle metamorphopsia during follow-up. Initial near-normal vision despite a striking macular lesion is a frequently tested paradox.<br><br>Peripheral field constriction (B) is more typical of retinitis pigmentosa. Severe ocular pain (A) and colored halos (E) suggest glaucoma or corneal disease rather than inherited macular dystrophy. Sudden total blindness (D) is extremely unusual in Best disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal structure is primarily dysfunctional in Best disease?",o:["Ganglion cell layer","Retinal pigment epithelium","Optic nerve fibers","Choroidal vasculature only","Inner nuclear layer"],a:1,e:"Best disease fundamentally results from retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction caused by abnormal bestrophin protein activity.<br><br>This dysfunction leads to impaired ion transport and accumulation of lipofuscin beneath the macula. Structural and functional retinal changes progressively impair central vision over time.<br><br>Optic nerve fibers (C) are primarily affected in optic neuropathies such as glaucoma. Choroidal vascular disease alone (D) is more relevant to wet ARMD than inherited vitelliform dystrophy. Ganglion cell pathology (A) does not produce classic egg-yolk lesions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality best demonstrates structural retinal changes in Best disease?",o:["OCT","Gonioscopy","Schirmer testing","Retinoscopy","Keratometry"],a:0,e:"OCT provides high-resolution cross-sectional imaging of vitelliform deposits, retinal layers, and associated atrophic or neovascular changes.<br><br>It is extremely useful for monitoring progression and identifying complications such as choroidal neovascularization or retinal fluid accumulation.<br><br>Gonioscopy (B) evaluates the anterior chamber angle. Schirmer testing (C) assesses tear secretion, while keratometry (E) measures corneal curvature rather than macular anatomy. Retinoscopy (D) evaluates refractive error only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature best differentiates Best disease from retinitis pigmentosa?",o:["Bilateral involvement","Genetic basis","Progressive visual dysfunction","Peripheral vision usually preserved","Retinal degeneration"],a:3,e:"Best disease primarily affects the macula and therefore preserves peripheral retinal function and side vision until relatively late stages.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa, in contrast, characteristically produces progressive peripheral field constriction and night blindness due to rod photoreceptor degeneration.<br><br>Both disorders may be hereditary (B), bilateral (A), and progressive (C), so those features alone do not reliably distinguish them. General retinal degeneration (E) occurs in both conditions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which stage of Best disease typically demonstrates layering of yellow material resembling a pseudohypopyon?",o:["Atrophic stage","Vitelliruptive stage","Pseudohypopyon stage","Fibrotic stage","End-stage cicatricial stage"],a:2,e:"In the pseudohypopyon stage, vitelliform material partially liquefies and settles inferiorly within the lesion, creating a layered appearance.<br><br>This stage reflects ongoing degeneration and redistribution of lipofuscin material beneath the retina.<br><br>The vitelliruptive stage (B) instead produces fragmented \"scrambled egg\" appearance. The atrophic stage (A) demonstrates retinal pigment epithelial degeneration rather than layering of material. Fibrotic stages (D, E) imply advanced scarring not characteristic of the classic pseudohypopyon phase.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced Best disease develops sudden decline in visual acuity due to subretinal hemorrhage. Which complication is most likely responsible?",o:["Retinal arterial occlusion","Choroidal neovascularization","Macular edema only","Optic neuritis","Vitreous degeneration"],a:1,e:"Choroidal neovascularization is a serious complication of advanced Best disease and may cause sudden visual deterioration from subretinal bleeding and leakage.<br><br>Anti-VEGF injections are now commonly used to manage these neovascular complications and preserve central vision. Advanced-stage sudden decline from choroidal neovascular membrane is an emphasised complication.<br><br>Retinal arterial occlusion (A) causes diffuse retinal ischemia rather than isolated subretinal hemorrhage. Optic neuritis (D) primarily causes painful visual loss and color desaturation. Vitreous degeneration (E) does not usually produce sudden submacular hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual field defect is most likely in advanced Best disease?",o:["Bitemporal hemianopia","Peripheral ring scotoma","Altitudinal field defect","Homonymous hemianopia","Central scotoma"],a:4,e:"Progressive macular degeneration in Best disease impairs foveal function and commonly produces central scotomas.<br><br>Patients experience difficulty reading and recognizing faces while maintaining relatively intact peripheral orientation vision.<br><br>Bitemporal hemianopia (A) suggests optic chiasmal pathology. Ring scotomas (B) are classically associated with retinitis pigmentosa. Homonymous hemianopia (D) indicates retrochiasmal neurological disease rather than macular pathology. Altitudinal defects (C) are more typical of ischemic optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding ERG in Best disease is most accurate?",o:["ERG is absent in all cases","ERG demonstrates severe rod dysfunction","ERG is pathognomonic for Best disease","ERG shows optic nerve conduction delay","ERG is usually normal"],a:4,e:"ERG is often normal because generalized retinal photoreceptor function remains relatively preserved despite retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction.<br><br>Severe rod dysfunction (B) is more characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. ERG does not assess optic nerve conduction delay (D). No ERG pattern is entirely pathognomonic for Best disease (C).<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which age group is most commonly affected by initial manifestations of Best disease?",o:["Neonates only","Elderly smokers only","Middle-aged diabetics only","Childhood and adolescence","Post-traumatic adults only"],a:3,e:"Best disease commonly manifests during childhood or adolescence, although severity and progression vary among affected individuals.<br><br>Fundus lesions may precede substantial visual complaints, making family screening important in genetically affected families.<br><br>Elderly smokers (B) are more typical of ARMD demographics. Trauma (E) and diabetes (C) do not cause inherited vitelliform dystrophy. Neonatal-only presentation (A) is uncommon.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is the closest clinical differential diagnosis of adult Best disease in elderly patients?",o:["Wet ARMD","Acute glaucoma","Papilledema","Keratoconus","Corneal ulcer"],a:0,e:"Adult vitelliform lesions and advanced Best disease may resemble wet ARMD because both can produce central visual loss, pigment epithelial abnormalities, and subretinal changes.<br><br>Detailed history, imaging, and electrophysiology help differentiate these conditions. Adult-onset foveomacular vitelliform dystrophy as the closest mimic is a recurring differential.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (B) causes painful red eye and elevated intraocular pressure rather than vitelliform lesions. Papilledema (C) affects the optic disc, while corneal ulceration (E) causes anterior segment inflammation. Keratoconus (D) is a corneal ectatic disorder unrelated to macular dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The characteristic \"egg-yolk\" lesion of Best disease is located primarily at the:",o:["Peripheral retina","Optic disc margin","Macula","Ora serrata","Vitreous base"],a:2,e:"Best disease selectively involves the macular region, producing the classic vitelliform lesion beneath the fovea.<br><br>Because the macula mediates detailed central vision, patients eventually develop reading difficulty and central distortion.<br><br>Peripheral retina (A) is usually relatively preserved. Optic disc lesions (B) are more relevant to papilledema or optic neuropathies. The ora serrata (D) and vitreous base (E) are peripheral structures unrelated to vitelliform macular deposits.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual function is relatively preserved until later stages of Best disease?",o:["Reading vision","Color discrimination","Contrast sensitivity","Peripheral orientation vision","Central acuity"],a:3,e:"Because Best disease primarily affects the macula, peripheral retinal function and orientation vision remain relatively intact until advanced stages.<br><br>Patients therefore retain mobility despite progressive central visual impairment.<br><br>Reading vision (A) and central acuity (E) are affected earlier because they depend heavily on foveal function. Contrast sensitivity (C) and color discrimination (B) may also deteriorate with macular degeneration.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which protein is defective in Best vitelliform macular dystrophy?",o:["Rhodopsin","Fibrillin","Myocilin","Collagen IV","Bestrophin-1"],a:4,e:"Mutations in the BEST1 gene produce abnormal bestrophin-1 protein within retinal pigment epithelial cells, leading to dysfunction and lipofuscin accumulation.<br><br>Rhodopsin mutations (A) are associated with some forms of retinitis pigmentosa. Myocilin (C) is linked to juvenile open-angle glaucoma. Fibrillin abnormalities (B) occur in Marfan syndrome. Collagen IV mutations (D) are associated with basement membrane disorders rather than vitelliform dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests progression of Best disease with macular involvement?",o:["Night blindness","Painful red eye","Progressive metamorphopsia","Colored halos","Peripheral flashes only"],a:2,e:"Metamorphopsia reflects progressive disruption of macular photoreceptor alignment and is a major symptom of worsening Best disease.<br><br>Amsler grid monitoring may help detect progression and neovascular complications during follow-up.<br><br>Night blindness (A) suggests rod dysfunction such as retinitis pigmentosa. Painful red eye (B) and colored halos (D) are more suggestive of glaucoma or corneal disease. Peripheral flashes (E) imply vitreoretinal traction rather than isolated macular dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which modality is most useful for monitoring development of choroidal neovascularization in Best disease?",o:["OCT and fluorescein angiography","Schirmer test","Gonioscopy","Keratometry","Hess chart"],a:0,e:"OCT identifies retinal fluid and structural distortion, while fluorescein angiography demonstrates leakage from choroidal neovascular membranes.<br><br>Together, these investigations are essential for monitoring progression and guiding anti-VEGF therapy in complicated Best disease.<br><br>Schirmer testing (B) evaluates tear production, gonioscopy (C) assesses the anterior chamber angle, and keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature. Hess charting (E) is used in ocular motility disorders rather than retinal disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease retains relatively good visual acuity despite obvious vitelliform lesions. Which explanation is most accurate?",o:["Optic nerve compensation occurs","Peripheral retina replaces macular function","Choroidal vessels bypass degeneration","Vitreous magnifies the retinal image","Early photoreceptor function may remain relatively preserved"],a:4,e:"In early Best disease, substantial vitelliform material may accumulate before severe photoreceptor dysfunction develops, allowing relatively preserved visual acuity initially.<br><br>Visual decline usually occurs gradually with progression of retinal pigment epithelial and photoreceptor degeneration.<br><br>Optic nerve compensation (A) does not bypass retinal pathology. Peripheral retina (B) cannot fully substitute for foveal detailed vision. Choroidal circulation (C) does not prevent macular degeneration, and vitreous magnification (D) has no protective visual role.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 16-year-old boy with Best disease develops gradual decline in reading vision. Fundoscopy demonstrates breakup of the vitelliform lesion into irregular yellow fragments. Which stage is most likely present?",o:["Atrophic stage","Vitelliform stage","Fibrotic stage","Pseudohypopyon stage","Vitelliruptive stage"],a:4,e:"The vitelliruptive stage represents fragmentation of vitelliform material, producing the classic \"scrambled egg\" appearance within the macula. This stage reflects progression of retinal pigment epithelial degeneration and disruption of lipofuscin deposits.<br><br>Visual acuity often begins deteriorating more significantly during this stage. Adolescent reading difficulty with a vitelliform lesion is a stem pattern examiners reuse.<br><br>The vitelliform stage (B) contains a more homogeneous egg-yolk lesion. Pseudohypopyon stage (D) demonstrates layering of material inferiorly rather than fragmented breakup. Atrophic stage (A) reflects later retinal pigment epithelial loss, while fibrotic stage (C) implies scar formation rather than classic fragmentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly supports the diagnosis of Best disease over Stargardt disease?",o:["Central visual impairment","Macular involvement","Bilateral retinal disease","Abnormal EOG with relatively normal ERG","Lipofuscin accumulation"],a:3,e:"Best disease characteristically produces a markedly abnormal electro-oculogram due to retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction, while ERG often remains relatively preserved.<br><br>Stargardt disease may also involve lipofuscin accumulation (E) and bilateral macular pathology (B, C). Central visual impairment (A) occurs in both diseases, so it does not reliably differentiate them.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Best disease develops sudden metamorphopsia and subretinal hemorrhage. Which complication should be suspected first?",o:["Optic neuritis","Retinal detachment","Choroidal neovascularization","CRAO","Papilledema"],a:2,e:"Choroidal neovascularization is a vision-threatening complication of advanced Best disease and may produce sudden distortion, hemorrhage, and rapid central visual decline.<br><br>Current management typically involves intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy. Sudden metamorphopsia from subretinal fluid signalling CNV is an emphasised red-flag transition.<br><br>CRAO (D) causes diffuse retinal ischemia and cherry-red spot rather than isolated subretinal hemorrhage. Optic neuritis (A) usually presents with painful eye movements and color desaturation. Papilledema (E) affects the optic disc rather than the macula.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal function generally remains preserved until relatively late in Best disease?",o:["Fine reading vision","Contrast sensitivity","Color discrimination","Central fixation","Peripheral orientation vision"],a:4,e:"Best disease selectively affects the macula, so peripheral retinal function and orientation vision are usually preserved until late stages.<br><br>Patients may therefore remain independently mobile despite significant difficulty with reading and facial recognition.<br><br>Reading vision (A) and central fixation (D) depend heavily on foveal integrity and are affected earlier. Contrast sensitivity (B) and color perception (C) may also deteriorate progressively because of central photoreceptor dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which fundoscopic appearance is most classically associated with the early vitelliform stage of Best disease?",o:["Bone-spicule pigmentation","Macular star","Egg-yolk lesion","Flame-shaped hemorrhages","Cotton wool spots"],a:2,e:"The classic vitelliform stage demonstrates a round yellow submacular lesion resembling egg yolk due to accumulation of lipofuscin beneath the retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Bone-spicule pigmentation (A) is characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Flame hemorrhages (D) and cotton wool spots (E) occur in retinal vascular disease. Macular star (B) is associated with neuroretinitis or severe hypertension.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which gene mutation is most commonly implicated in Best vitelliform macular dystrophy?",o:["PAX6","RB1","ABCA4","BEST1","MYOC"],a:3,e:"Best disease is caused primarily by mutations in the BEST1 gene, which encodes bestrophin-1 protein located within retinal pigment epithelial cells.<br><br>Defective bestrophin function impairs retinal pigment epithelial physiology and promotes lipofuscin accumulation beneath the macula.<br><br>ABCA4 mutations (C) are classically associated with Stargardt disease. MYOC mutations (E) are linked to juvenile open-angle glaucoma. RB1 mutations (B) occur in retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young patient with Best disease has surprisingly good visual acuity despite dramatic macular lesions. Which explanation is most accurate?",o:["Peripheral retina fully replaces macular function","Optic nerve bypasses damaged retina","Early photoreceptor function may remain relatively preserved","Corneal magnification improves acuity","Choroidal circulation compensates completely"],a:2,e:"In early Best disease, substantial vitelliform deposits may be present before severe photoreceptor dysfunction develops, allowing relatively preserved visual acuity.<br><br>Peripheral retina (A) cannot replace detailed foveal vision. Optic nerve bypass mechanisms (B) do not exist. Corneal optics (D) and choroidal circulation (E) cannot prevent progressive macular degeneration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which electrophysiological test directly evaluates retinal pigment epithelial function in Best disease?",o:["ERG","VEP","Amsler grid","Humphrey perimetry","Electro-oculography"],a:4,e:"Electro-oculography specifically evaluates retinal pigment epithelial integrity and demonstrates reduced Arden ratio in Best disease.<br><br>Many recall discussions emphasize \"abnormal EOG with normal ERG\" as a one-line favorite question.<br><br>ERG (A) primarily assesses generalized retinal photoreceptor function. VEP (B) evaluates visual pathway conduction. Amsler grid (C) detects metamorphopsia but does not measure retinal pigment epithelial physiology.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual symptom most strongly indicates progressive macular involvement in Best disease?",o:["Peripheral flashes","Night blindness","Diplopia","Progressive metamorphopsia","Painful red eye"],a:3,e:"Progressive distortion of central vision reflects worsening disruption of macular architecture and photoreceptor alignment in Best disease.<br><br>Patients frequently describe wavy lines or distorted reading text. Amsler grid testing may reveal early progression before major acuity decline occurs.<br><br>Night blindness (B) suggests rod dysfunction such as retinitis pigmentosa. Diplopia (C) indicates ocular misalignment rather than macular disease. Painful red eye (E) suggests anterior segment pathology instead of inherited dystrophy. Peripheral flashes (A) imply vitreoretinal traction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced Best disease develops retinal pigment epithelial atrophy. Which visual defect is most likely?",o:["Homonymous hemianopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Altitudinal defect","Central scotoma"],a:4,e:"Macular degeneration and retinal pigment epithelial atrophy impair foveal function, producing central scotomas and severe reading difficulty.<br><br>Patients may still maintain peripheral navigation ability because side vision remains relatively preserved. Late RPE atrophy producing irreversible loss is a recurring prognostic teaching point.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia (A) results from retrochiasmal neurological lesions. Ring scotomas (C) are characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Altitudinal defects (D) are more typical of ischemic optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which stage of Best disease demonstrates inferior layering of vitelliform material?",o:["Fibrotic stage","Vitelliruptive stage","Pseudohypopyon stage","Atrophic stage","End-stage scar stage"],a:2,e:"In the pseudohypopyon stage, partially liquefied vitelliform material settles inferiorly within the lesion, creating a layered appearance resembling hypopyon.<br><br>Vitelliruptive stage (B) demonstrates fragmented \"scrambled egg\" appearance rather than layering. Atrophic stage (D) shows retinal pigment epithelial degeneration, while fibrotic stages (A, E) imply advanced scarring rather than classic layered deposits.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most useful for monitoring retinal structural progression in Best disease?",o:["OCT","Gonioscopy","Schirmer testing","Pachymetry","Keratometry"],a:0,e:"Optical coherence tomography provides detailed cross-sectional imaging of vitelliform deposits, retinal layers, fluid accumulation, and atrophic progression.<br><br>It is now indispensable in monitoring disease progression and detecting complications such as choroidal neovascularization.<br><br>Gonioscopy (B) evaluates the anterior chamber angle. Pachymetry (D) measures corneal thickness, while keratometry (E) measures corneal curvature. Schirmer testing (C) assesses tear production.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding peripheral retina in Best disease is most accurate?",o:["Peripheral retina is usually severely ischemic","Peripheral degeneration dominates early disease","Peripheral retinal detachment is inevitable","Peripheral tears are universal","Peripheral retina remains relatively preserved"],a:4,e:"Best disease selectively involves the macula, so peripheral retinal function usually remains intact for prolonged periods.<br><br>Patients therefore maintain orientation and mobility despite progressive loss of detailed central visual tasks.<br><br>Peripheral ischemia (A) is more relevant to vascular occlusive disease. Peripheral degeneration (B) and ring scotomas are characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa rather than Best disease. Retinal detachment (C) is not inevitable.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition most commonly enters differential diagnosis with adult-onset vitelliform lesions?",o:["Acute angle closure glaucoma","Wet ARMD","Papilledema","Corneal ulcer","Keratoconus"],a:1,e:"Adult-onset vitelliform lesions may mimic wet ARMD because both disorders can produce central visual impairment and subretinal macular abnormalities.<br><br>Careful history, age profile, imaging, and electrophysiology help differentiate inherited dystrophy from acquired neovascular degeneration.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (A) presents with painful red eye and raised intraocular pressure. Papilledema (C) affects the optic disc rather than the macula. Keratoconus (E) and corneal ulceration (D) are corneal diseases unrelated to vitelliform dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which protein is abnormal in Best vitelliform macular dystrophy?",o:["Rhodopsin","Peripherin","Myocilin","Bestrophin-1","Fibrillin"],a:3,e:"Bestrophin-1 is the retinal pigment epithelial protein encoded by the BEST1 gene and is dysfunctional in Best disease.<br><br>Defective ion transport and retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction lead to accumulation of lipofuscin beneath the macula.<br><br>Rhodopsin mutations (A) are associated with certain forms of retinitis pigmentosa. Myocilin (C) is linked to juvenile glaucoma. Fibrillin abnormalities (E) occur in Marfan syndrome.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual function is typically impaired earliest in Best disease?",o:["Peripheral field awareness","Dark adaptation","Reading acuity","Ocular motility","Corneal sensation"],a:2,e:"Macular dysfunction first impairs detailed central tasks such as reading because the fovea mediates highest visual acuity.<br><br>Patients may complain of blurred central text and distorted lines long before major peripheral visual difficulties occur.<br><br>Peripheral awareness (A) is usually preserved until later stages. Dark adaptation (B) is more strongly affected in rod dystrophies. Ocular motility (D) and corneal sensation (E) are unrelated to Best disease pathophysiology.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which age group most classically demonstrates the initial vitelliform lesion in Best disease?",o:["Neonates only","Elderly smokers","Childhood or adolescence","Post-traumatic adults","Diabetic adults only"],a:2,e:"Best disease usually manifests during childhood or adolescence, though severity and progression vary substantially among patients.<br><br>Fundoscopic abnormalities may appear before major symptoms, making family screening clinically important. The childhood vitelliform stage as the initial presentation is a classic age-correlation fact.<br><br>Elderly smokers (B) are more characteristic of ARMD demographics. Trauma (D) and diabetes (E) do not produce inherited vitelliform dystrophy. Neonatal-only presentation (A) is uncommon.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which complication most commonly causes sudden visual deterioration in advanced Best disease?",o:["Acute glaucoma","Choroidal neovascular membrane formation","Retinal artery embolism","Corneal hydrops","Optic chiasmal compression"],a:1,e:"Development of choroidal neovascularization may cause leakage and subretinal hemorrhage, producing abrupt central visual decline.<br><br>Anti-VEGF therapy is now standard management for this complication and is increasingly emphasized in modern retina recalls. Choroidal neovascular membrane as the chief cause of sudden deterioration is heavily emphasised.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (A) produces painful visual loss rather than isolated macular hemorrhage. Corneal hydrops (D) occurs in keratoconus. Optic chiasmal compression (E) causes bitemporal hemianopia instead of focal macular complications.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding night vision in Best disease is most accurate?",o:["Severe nyctalopia occurs early","Peripheral rod degeneration dominates disease","Rod function is completely abolished","Night vision loss precedes macular lesions","Night blindness is usually absent initially"],a:4,e:"Best disease primarily affects the macula and retinal pigment epithelium rather than generalized rod photoreceptor function, so night vision often remains relatively preserved initially.<br><br>This distinction helps differentiate Best disease from rod-cone dystrophies such as retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br>Severe nyctalopia (A) and peripheral rod degeneration (B) are characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa. Night vision loss preceding lesions (D) is not typical of Best disease progression.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A teenager with Best disease demonstrates markedly abnormal EOG but preserved ERG. Which explanation is most accurate?",o:["Optic nerve disease predominates","Generalized retinal failure is complete","Corneal conduction is defective","Retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction exceeds photoreceptor dysfunction","Choroidal ischemia selectively spares retina"],a:3,e:"Best disease primarily involves retinal pigment epithelial dysfunction, which profoundly affects EOG results while generalized photoreceptor function measured by ERG may remain relatively preserved initially.<br><br>Optic nerve disease (A) does not explain abnormal EOG findings. Complete generalized retinal failure (B) would severely impair ERG as well. Corneal conduction abnormalities (C) are irrelevant to retinal electrophysiology, and choroidal ischemia (E) is not the fundamental disease mechanism.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old highly myopic patient complains of sudden flashes of light, floaters, and a curtain descending over one eye. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["CRAO","Acute glaucoma","Optic neuritis","Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment","Central serous chorioretinopathy"],a:3,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment (RRD) occurs when a retinal tear allows liquefied vitreous to enter the subretinal space, separating the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium. Flashes, floaters, and curtain-like visual field loss are classic symptoms.<br><br>High myopia is among the strongest predisposing factors because elongated axial length promotes lattice degeneration and retinal breaks.<br><br>CRAO (A) causes sudden profound visual loss with cherry-red spot rather than photopsia and floaters. Acute glaucoma (B) presents with painful red eye and halos. Optic neuritis (C) usually causes painful eye movements and color desaturation rather than curtain-like field defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of retinal detachment is caused by a retinal break?",o:["Exudative retinal detachment","Tractional retinal detachment","Serous retinal detachment","Secondary retinal detachment","Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment"],a:4,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment specifically requires a retinal tear or hole through which vitreous fluid gains access to the subretinal space. It is the commonest type of retinal detachment.<br><br>Tractional detachment (B) results from fibrovascular pulling without retinal breaks, commonly in proliferative diabetic retinopathy. Exudative detachments (A, C) occur due to subretinal fluid accumulation without retinal tears. \"Secondary retinal detachment\" (D) is nonspecific terminology rather than a mechanistic category.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy develops retinal elevation due to fibrovascular contraction. Which type of detachment is most likely?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Tractional","Combined rhegmatogenous-exudative","Serous"],a:2,e:"Tractional retinal detachment occurs when fibrovascular membranes contract and mechanically pull the retina away from the underlying retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Proliferative diabetic retinopathy is the commonest cause. Unlike rhegmatogenous detachments, photopsia may be absent because retinal tears are not necessary. Recurrent vitreous haemorrhage driving repeated intervention in PDR is a recurring management theme.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachment (A) requires a retinal break. Exudative or serous detachments (B, E) result from fluid leakage rather than traction. Combined detachments (D) may occur later but are not the primary mechanism described here.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is commonly absent in tractional retinal detachment?",o:["Visual field defect","Reduced visual acuity","Floaters","Photopsia","Metamorphopsia"],a:3,e:"Photopsia usually results from vitreoretinal traction causing retinal stimulation during retinal tear formation. Because tractional detachments may occur without retinal breaks, flashes are often absent.<br><br>Visual field loss (A) commonly occurs once the retina detaches. Reduced acuity (B) may develop if the macula becomes involved. Floaters (C) can still occur due to associated vitreous changes, so they are not characteristically absent.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment describes a \"black curtain\" progressing across vision. This symptom most directly represents:",o:["Corneal edema","Vitreous hemorrhage","Progressive retinal separation","Optic nerve ischemia","Choroidal rupture"],a:2,e:"As the retina detaches progressively, patients perceive an enlarging shadow or curtain corresponding to the expanding detached retinal area and associated field loss.<br><br>This symptom is considered a major warning sign requiring urgent retinal evaluation. Delayed treatment significantly worsens visual prognosis, especially if the macula detaches.<br><br>Corneal edema (A) causes halos and blurred vision rather than field-shadow progression. Vitreous hemorrhage (B) typically causes diffuse haze or floaters rather than a progressive curtain. Optic nerve ischemia (D) produces different field patterns rather than classic retinal detachment symptoms.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which risk factor is strongly associated with rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Hyperopia","Episcleritis","Chronic dacryocystitis","Cataract alone without surgery","High myopia"],a:4,e:"High myopia predisposes to retinal thinning, lattice degeneration, posterior vitreous detachment, and retinal tears, all of which increase risk for rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Hyperopia (A) is not a classic risk factor for RRD. Episcleritis (B) and dacryocystitis (C) are anterior segment disorders unrelated to retinal tearing mechanisms. Cataract itself (D) is less important than cataract surgery-associated vitreous changes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is considered the gold standard for diagnosing retinal detachment?",o:["OCT","CT orbit","B-scan ultrasonography","Dilated fundus examination with indirect ophthalmoscopy","Visual evoked potential"],a:3,e:"Indirect ophthalmoscopy with scleral depression allows direct visualization of retinal tears, retinal elevation, and peripheral retinal pathology, making it the diagnostic gold standard.<br><br>B-scan ultrasound (C) is extremely useful when media opacity obscures retinal view, but it is not the primary gold standard when direct visualization is possible. OCT (A) mainly evaluates macular structure rather than peripheral retinal tears. CT orbit (B) is not routinely used for retinal detachment diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with exudative retinal detachment most characteristically demonstrates:",o:["Retinal tear","Fibrovascular traction","Shifting subretinal fluid","Giant retinal break","Vitreous incarceration"],a:2,e:"Exudative retinal detachment occurs because fluid accumulates beneath the retina without retinal tears or traction. The fluid may shift with gravity and body position.<br><br>Retinal tears (A) define rhegmatogenous detachments. Fibrovascular traction (B) occurs in tractional detachments. Giant retinal breaks (D) are severe rhegmatogenous lesions rather than exudative phenomena.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment is most commonly associated with proliferative diabetic retinopathy?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Giant retinal tear detachment","Serous","Tractional"],a:4,e:"Fibrovascular proliferation in proliferative diabetic retinopathy contracts and exerts traction on the retina, producing tractional retinal detachment.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) primarily result from retinal breaks. Exudative detachments (B, D) are caused by inflammatory, vascular, or neoplastic leakage rather than fibrovascular contraction. Giant retinal tears (C) represent a rhegmatogenous subtype.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal finding is most characteristic of long-standing rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Papilledema","Intraretinal cysts","Macular star","Hard drusen","Roth spots"],a:1,e:"Long-standing retinal detachments may develop degenerative intraretinal cysts due to chronic retinal separation and atrophy.<br><br>Papilledema (A) reflects optic disc swelling. Drusen (D) occur in ARMD, while Roth spots (E) are retinal hemorrhages with pale centers classically seen in infective endocarditis. Macular star (C) is associated with neuroretinitis or severe hypertension.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which surgical procedure is commonly preferred for uncomplicated rhegmatogenous retinal detachment with peripheral retinal break?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Dacryocystorhinostomy","Keratoplasty","Cyclocryotherapy","Scleral buckling"],a:4,e:"Scleral buckling indents the sclera externally to support closure of retinal breaks and reduce vitreoretinal traction in uncomplicated rhegmatogenous retinal detachments.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (A) treats glaucoma, while keratoplasty (C) addresses corneal disease. DCR (B) is lacrimal surgery unrelated to retinal pathology. Cyclocryotherapy (D) is not standard primary management for uncomplicated RRD.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type typically demonstrates a concave retinal configuration?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Tractional","Giant tear detachment","Bullous retinal detachment"],a:2,e:"Tractional detachments classically appear concave because fibrovascular membranes pull the retina inward toward the vitreous cavity.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) are usually corrugated and convex because subretinal fluid accumulates through retinal tears. Exudative detachments (B) are typically smooth and bullous due to shifting fluid.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom combination most strongly suggests posterior vitreous detachment with retinal tear risk?",o:["Pain and redness","Excessive tearing only","Diplopia and ptosis","Halos and headache","Floaters and flashes"],a:4,e:"Posterior vitreous detachment may produce floaters from vitreous condensations and flashes due to vitreoretinal traction. Retinal tears may subsequently develop.<br><br>Pain and redness (A) suggest inflammatory or glaucomatous disease. Diplopia and ptosis (C) imply neurological or muscular pathology. Halos with headache (D) are more typical of acute angle closure glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment has macular involvement. Which prognostic statement is most accurate?",o:["Prognosis is unchanged","Visual prognosis worsens significantly","Peripheral vision only is affected","Surgery is contraindicated","Retina cannot be reattached"],a:1,e:"Macula-off retinal detachments have substantially poorer visual outcomes because prolonged foveal separation damages photoreceptors and retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Peripheral-only involvement (C) is incorrect once the macula detaches. Surgery (D) remains essential rather than contraindicated. Retinal reattachment (E) is often technically achievable even though visual recovery may be limited.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is most strongly associated with exudative retinal detachment due to malignancy?",o:["Keratoconus","Choroidal melanoma","Acute conjunctivitis","Retinitis pigmentosa","Episcleritis"],a:1,e:"Choroidal melanoma may produce exudative retinal detachment because tumor-associated vascular leakage causes accumulation of subretinal fluid.<br><br>Retinitis pigmentosa (D) primarily causes retinal degeneration and night blindness. Keratoconus (A) and episcleritis (E) are unrelated anterior segment conditions. Acute conjunctivitis (C) does not produce retinal detachment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type most commonly lacks retinal breaks?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Giant retinal tear detachment","Aphakic retinal detachment","Lattice-associated detachment","Tractional and exudative"],a:4,e:"Tractional detachments result from fibrovascular pulling, while exudative detachments arise from subretinal fluid accumulation; neither fundamentally requires retinal tears.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) by definition require retinal breaks. Giant retinal tears (B) are extreme forms of retinal breaks. Aphakic detachments (C) are usually rhegmatogenous rather than break-free.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which complication may develop after retinal detachment surgery due to proliferative membrane formation?",o:["PVR (proliferative vitreoretinopathy)","Corneal hydrops","Optic glioma","Dacryocystitis","Papillitis"],a:0,e:"Proliferative vitreoretinopathy (PVR) occurs when proliferative membranes contract on retinal surfaces after detachment or surgery, causing recurrent traction and redetachment.<br><br>Corneal hydrops (B) occurs in keratoconus. Optic glioma (C) and papillitis (E) are unrelated neurological/optic conditions. Dacryocystitis (D) is lacrimal sac infection unrelated to vitreoretinal surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which patient is at highest risk of rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Hyperopic child","Young emmetrope","Elderly high myope after cataract surgery","Mild allergic conjunctivitis patient","Chronic blepharitis patient"],a:2,e:"High myopia, aging-related vitreous degeneration, and previous cataract surgery all markedly increase risk for retinal tears and rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Allergic conjunctivitis (D) and blepharitis (E) are anterior segment inflammatory disorders unrelated to retinal tearing mechanisms. Young emmetropes (B) carry much lower risk. Identifying the highest-risk profile for rhegmatogenous detachment is a classic risk-stratification question.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which treatment modality involves intravitreal gas injection to repair selected retinal detachments?",o:["Pneumatic retinopexy","Trabeculectomy","Keratoplasty","Cyclodialysis","DCR"],a:0,e:"Pneumatic retinopexy uses intravitreal gas injection combined with retinal break sealing to reattach selected uncomplicated retinal detachments.<br><br>It is most suitable for superior retinal breaks and requires strict postoperative positioning.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (B) treats glaucoma. Keratoplasty (C) treats corneal pathology. DCR (E) is lacrimal surgery unrelated to retinal reattachment. Cyclodialysis (D) is unrelated to retinal detachment repair.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment demonstrates tobacco dust cells in the anterior vitreous. This sign most strongly suggests:",o:["Corneal ulceration","Retinal tear","Optic neuritis","Macular degeneration","Uveitis only"],a:1,e:"Pigmented tobacco dust cells (Shafer sign) in the anterior vitreous strongly suggest retinal pigment epithelial cells released from a retinal break or tear.<br><br>Corneal ulceration (A) and uveitis (E) may produce inflammatory cells but not characteristic retinal pigment dispersion. Optic neuritis (C) and macular degeneration (D) do not produce Shafer sign.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old pseudophakic patient complains of sudden onset flashes, floaters, and progressive superior visual field loss. Fundoscopy reveals an inferior horseshoe retinal tear with retinal elevation. Which type of retinal detachment is most likely?",o:["Exudative retinal detachment","Tractional retinal detachment","Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment","Serous choroidal detachment","Retinoschisis"],a:2,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment occurs when a retinal break allows liquefied vitreous to enter the subretinal space, separating the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium. Horseshoe tears are classic causative lesions.<br><br>Previous cataract surgery is a major risk factor because vitreous changes after surgery increase risk of retinal tears.<br><br>Tractional detachment (B) results from fibrovascular pulling without retinal breaks. Exudative detachments (A) occur due to subretinal fluid leakage without tears. Retinoschisis (E) involves splitting of retinal layers rather than true retinal separation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests an acute retinal tear preceding retinal detachment?",o:["Colored halos","Severe ocular pain","Flashes of light","Excessive lacrimation","Horizontal diplopia"],a:2,e:"Photopsia occurs because vitreoretinal traction mechanically stimulates retinal photoreceptors during posterior vitreous detachment or retinal tear formation.<br><br>Flashes combined with floaters are considered an ophthalmic warning sign requiring urgent dilated retinal examination.<br><br>Colored halos (A) are more suggestive of corneal edema or acute glaucoma. Severe pain (B) is uncommon in retinal detachment. Diplopia (E) usually reflects ocular motility disorders rather than retinal pathology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient develops concave retinal elevation due to fibrovascular membrane contraction. Which retinal detachment type is most likely?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Tractional","Giant retinal tear detachment","Bullous detachment"],a:2,e:"Tractional retinal detachment occurs when contracting fibrovascular membranes mechanically pull the retina away from the retinal pigment epithelium. The detached retina typically appears concave.<br><br>Proliferative diabetic retinopathy remains the commonest cause. The concave tractional detachment of advanced PDR is an instantly recognisable configuration.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) usually appear corrugated and convex because fluid accumulates through retinal breaks. Exudative detachments (B) are smooth and bullous due to subretinal fluid leakage rather than traction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type most commonly demonstrates shifting fluid with change in posture?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Tractional","Giant retinal tear detachment","Exudative","Combined traction-rhegmatogenous"],a:3,e:"Exudative retinal detachment occurs because fluid accumulates beneath the retina from inflammatory, vascular, or neoplastic leakage. Since the fluid is free-flowing, it may shift with gravity and body position.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) involve retinal tears and fixed subretinal fluid patterns. Tractional detachments (B) are mechanically tethered by fibrovascular membranes and therefore do not show characteristic shifting fluid.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment has central visual acuity preserved. Which statement is most accurate?",o:["Macula is still attached","Retinal break is absent","Optic nerve is unaffected","Choroid is detached instead","Vitreous hemorrhage is mandatory"],a:0,e:"If the macula remains attached (\"macula-on detachment\"), central visual acuity may remain relatively preserved despite peripheral retinal separation.<br><br>This is a major surgical emergency because prompt repair before macular involvement significantly improves visual prognosis. Retina surgeons strongly prioritize urgent intervention in macula-on detachments.<br><br>Retinal breaks (B) may still be present in rhegmatogenous detachments despite preserved acuity. Optic nerve integrity (C) does not explain preserved central vision specifically. Choroidal detachment (D) is a different pathology. Vitreous hemorrhage (E) is not mandatory.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal lesion most strongly predisposes to rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Hard drusen","Retinal hemorrhages","Cotton wool spots","Macular star","Lattice degeneration"],a:4,e:"Lattice degeneration produces peripheral retinal thinning and vitreoretinal adhesion, greatly increasing risk for retinal tears and subsequent rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Hard drusen (A) are associated with ARMD rather than retinal tearing. Cotton wool spots (C) and retinal hemorrhages (B) indicate retinal vascular ischemia, not vitreoretinal degeneration. Macular star (D) occurs in neuroretinitis or severe hypertension.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most useful when dense vitreous hemorrhage obscures retinal visualization in suspected retinal detachment?",o:["OCT","Fundus photography","Fluorescein angiography","B-scan ultrasonography","Retinoscopy"],a:3,e:"B-scan ultrasound is extremely valuable when media opacity prevents direct retinal visualization. It can identify retinal detachment, vitreous hemorrhage, and posterior vitreous detachment.<br><br>This investigation is.<br><br>OCT (A) requires relatively clear media and mainly assesses macular architecture. Fluorescein angiography (C) cannot adequately evaluate detached retina through dense hemorrhage. Retinoscopy (E) evaluates refractive status only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which surgical procedure involves external indentation of sclera to support retinal tear closure?",o:["Vitrectomy","Pneumatic retinopexy","Scleral buckling","Trabeculectomy","Cyclophotocoagulation"],a:2,e:"Scleral buckling creates external scleral indentation to relieve vitreoretinal traction and support closure of retinal breaks.<br><br>Vitrectomy (A) removes vitreous traction internally rather than externally indenting sclera. Pneumatic retinopexy (B) uses intravitreal gas instead of scleral buckle support. Trabeculectomy (D) treats glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type most commonly occurs in proliferative diabetic retinopathy?",o:["Exudative","Rhegmatogenous","Bullous","Serous","Tractional"],a:4,e:"Fibrovascular proliferation in proliferative diabetic retinopathy contracts progressively and pulls the retina from its underlying support, producing tractional detachment.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (B) require retinal tears, while exudative detachments (A) arise from subretinal fluid leakage without fibrovascular traction. Bullous detachments (C) are descriptive rather than mechanistic terminology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is least characteristic of retinal detachment?",o:["Curtain-like visual field loss","Flashes and floaters","Sudden severe ocular pain","Progressive peripheral field defect","Reduced visual acuity"],a:2,e:"Retinal detachment is typically painless because the retina lacks pain fibers. Patients more commonly report flashes, floaters, peripheral field loss, or curtain-like shadows.<br><br>Curtain-like field defects (A), flashes/floaters (B), and progressive field loss (D) are classic retinal detachment symptoms. Visual acuity reduction (E) occurs particularly when the macula becomes involved.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which postoperative complication is most feared after retinal detachment repair because it may cause recurrent detachment?",o:["Corneal hydrops","Papillitis","Dacryocystitis","Episcleritis","Proliferative vitreoretinopathy"],a:4,e:"Proliferative vitreoretinopathy (PVR) involves formation and contraction of proliferative membranes on retinal surfaces after detachment or surgery, causing recurrent traction and redetachment.<br><br>Corneal hydrops (A) is associated with keratoconus. Dacryocystitis (C) and episcleritis (D) are anterior segment disorders unrelated to vitreoretinal surgery. Papillitis (B) involves optic nerve inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with superior retinal detachment most likely notices visual field loss in which area initially?",o:["Superior field","Central field only","Temporal field only","Nasal field only","Inferior field"],a:4,e:"Retinal images are inverted, so superior retinal pathology produces inferior visual field defects.<br><br>Superior field defects (A) would correspond more closely to inferior retinal involvement. Central-only defects (B) usually imply isolated macular pathology rather than broad superior detachment. Nasal and temporal isolated losses (D, E) are not universally expected here.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal finding strongly suggests chronic retinal detachment?",o:["Intraretinal cyst formation","Cherry-red spot","Roth spots","Drusen only","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Long-standing retinal detachment may produce degenerative intraretinal cysts due to chronic retinal separation and atrophy.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (B) is characteristic of CRAO. Roth spots (C) occur in infective endocarditis and hematologic disorders. Drusen (D) are associated with ARMD. Papilledema (E) reflects optic disc swelling.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which patient profile carries highest risk for retinal detachment?",o:["Hyperopic young adult","Mild allergic conjunctivitis patient","High myope after cataract surgery","Chronic blepharitis patient","Episcleritis patient"],a:2,e:"High myopia predisposes to lattice degeneration and retinal tears, while cataract surgery accelerates vitreous changes that increase retinal detachment risk.<br><br>Allergic conjunctivitis (B), blepharitis (D), and episcleritis (E) are anterior segment inflammatory disorders unrelated to retinal tearing mechanisms. Hyperopia (A) is not a classic major RRD risk factor.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment surgery requires strict postoperative head positioning?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Cyclodialysis","DCR","Penetrating keratoplasty","Pneumatic retinopexy"],a:4,e:"Pneumatic retinopexy uses intravitreal gas to tamponade retinal breaks, making postoperative positioning essential for successful retinal reattachment.<br><br>Patients are carefully instructed regarding posture depending on retinal break location.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (A) is glaucoma surgery. DCR (C) addresses nasolacrimal obstruction. Penetrating keratoplasty (D) treats corneal disease rather than retinal detachment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type usually appears smooth and bullous ophthalmoscopically?",o:["Tractional","Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Combined tractional-rhegmatogenous","Retinoschisis"],a:2,e:"Exudative retinal detachments classically appear smooth and bullous because fluid accumulates beneath the retina without retinal breaks or tractional tethering.<br><br>Tractional detachments (A) usually appear concave due to fibrovascular pulling. Rhegmatogenous detachments (B) are typically corrugated because of subretinal fluid passing through retinal tears. Retinoschisis (E) represents retinal layer splitting rather than true detachment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests macular involvement in retinal detachment?",o:["Flashes only","Peripheral floaters only","Excessive tearing","Mild itching","Severe reduction in central vision"],a:4,e:"Once the macula detaches, central visual acuity deteriorates markedly because the fovea is responsible for detailed vision.<br><br>Macula-off detachments carry significantly poorer visual prognosis, making urgent diagnosis and management critical.<br><br>Flashes (A) and floaters (B) may occur before macular involvement and are less predictive of severe central acuity loss. Itching (D) and tearing (C) are anterior segment symptoms unrelated to retinal separation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which sign strongly indicates retinal tear in a patient with flashes and floaters?",o:["Shafer sign","Kayser-Fleischer ring","Argyll Robertson pupil","Marcus Gunn pupil","Bitot spots"],a:0,e:"Shafer sign refers to tobacco dust pigment cells floating in the anterior vitreous, indicating release of retinal pigment epithelial cells from a retinal tear.<br><br>Kayser-Fleischer rings (B) occur in Wilson disease. Marcus Gunn pupil (D) indicates RAPD. Bitot spots (E) occur in vitamin A deficiency. Argyll Robertson pupil (C) is associated with neurosyphilis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which mechanism best explains rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Choroidal tumor leakage","Fibrovascular membrane contraction","Retinal break allowing vitreous fluid under retina","Optic disc edema","Corneal endothelial failure"],a:2,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment fundamentally requires a retinal break through which liquefied vitreous enters the subretinal space.<br><br>Posterior vitreous detachment and lattice degeneration commonly predispose to this mechanism.<br><br>Choroidal tumor leakage (A) causes exudative detachment. Fibrovascular contraction (B) produces tractional detachment. Optic disc edema (D) and corneal endothelial failure (E) are unrelated mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding retinal detachment prognosis is most accurate?",o:["Visual prognosis depends heavily on macular status","All detachments have identical prognosis","Peripheral retina determines central acuity only","Surgery is ineffective once retina detaches","Retinal tears always heal spontaneously"],a:0,e:"Macular involvement is the single most important prognostic factor in retinal detachment because prolonged foveal separation damages photoreceptors and retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Early repair before macular detachment offers the best chance of preserving high-quality central vision.<br><br>Detachments do not share identical prognosis (B). Surgery (D) remains highly effective in many cases. Retinal tears (E) do not reliably heal spontaneously and may progress dangerously without treatment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old pseudophakic patient presents with sudden flashes, numerous floaters, and a dark curtain descending from above. Indirect ophthalmoscopy reveals a superior horseshoe tear with mobile corrugated retina. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Exudative retinal detachment","Tractional retinal detachment","Choroidal detachment","Retinoschisis","Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment"],a:4,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment occurs when a retinal break permits liquefied vitreous to enter the subretinal space. Horseshoe tears are classic lesions, especially in pseudophakic or highly myopic patients.<br><br>Superior tears often produce inferior visual field defects because retinal images are inverted.<br><br>Tractional detachment (B) occurs from fibrovascular pulling without retinal tears. Exudative detachment (A) demonstrates shifting fluid rather than corrugated mobile retina. Retinoschisis (D) causes retinal splitting rather than true neurosensory retinal separation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type classically demonstrates smooth bullous elevation with shifting fluid?",o:["Tractional retinal detachment","Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment","Giant retinal tear detachment","Exudative retinal detachment","Combined retinal detachment"],a:3,e:"Exudative retinal detachment occurs because fluid leaks beneath the retina from inflammatory, vascular, or neoplastic causes without retinal tears or vitreoretinal traction.<br><br>The detached retina appears smooth and bullous, and subretinal fluid may shift with gravity.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (B) are usually corrugated due to retinal breaks. Tractional detachments (A) appear concave because fibrovascular membranes pull the retina inward. Giant retinal tears (C) still represent rhegmatogenous pathology rather than free shifting fluid.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy develops progressive retinal elevation without retinal breaks. Which mechanism is most responsible?",o:["Choroidal exudation","Vitreous liquefaction only","Fibrovascular membrane contraction","Retinal arterial occlusion","Corneal endothelial failure"],a:2,e:"Tractional retinal detachment in proliferative diabetic retinopathy occurs because fibrovascular membranes progressively contract and mechanically elevate the retina.<br><br>Choroidal exudation (A) produces exudative rather than tractional detachment. Vitreous liquefaction alone (B) is insufficient without traction. Retinal arterial occlusion (D) causes ischemia, not fibrovascular tractional elevation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal break is most commonly associated with rhegmatogenous retinal detachment?",o:["Operculated tear","Macular hole only","Retinal dialysis","Atrophic hole","Horseshoe tear"],a:4,e:"Horseshoe retinal tears result from persistent vitreoretinal traction and are the most common retinal breaks leading to rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Prompt laser or surgical treatment is essential.<br><br>Operculated tears (A) may have lower traction after avulsion. Retinal dialysis (C) is more commonly associated with trauma. Macular holes (B) are less common causes of generalized retinal detachment.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom most strongly suggests macula-off retinal detachment?",o:["Mild itching","Severe reduction of central visual acuity","Colored halos","Painful red eye","Diplopia"],a:1,e:"Once the macula detaches, central detailed vision declines dramatically because foveal photoreceptors become separated from the retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Macular status is the single most important prognostic factor in retinal detachment surgery.<br><br>Painful red eye (D) suggests glaucoma or inflammation. Colored halos (C) are associated with corneal edema. Diplopia (E) usually reflects ocular motility disorders rather than retinal pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which examination technique remains the gold standard for identifying peripheral retinal tears?",o:["OCT","CT orbit","MRI orbit","Indirect ophthalmoscopy with scleral depression","Retinoscopy"],a:3,e:"Indirect ophthalmoscopy with scleral depression allows dynamic visualization of peripheral retina and retinal breaks, making it the gold standard clinical examination.<br><br>Recognition of peripheral retinal pathology is a core retina skill.<br><br>OCT (A) mainly evaluates macular architecture. CT and MRI (B, C) are not standard retinal tear investigations. Retinoscopy (E) evaluates refractive error only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type most classically appears concave ophthalmoscopically?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Exudative","Serous","Bullous","Tractional"],a:4,e:"Tractional retinal detachments appear concave because fibrovascular membranes tether and pull the retina inward toward the vitreous cavity.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) are usually convex and corrugated due to subretinal fluid accumulation. Exudative detachments (B) are smooth and bullous because fluid accumulates freely beneath the retina.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition most strongly predisposes to giant retinal tears?",o:["Hyperopia","Acute conjunctivitis","High myopia","Episcleritis","Chalazion"],a:2,e:"High myopia predisposes to peripheral retinal thinning, vitreoretinal degeneration, and giant retinal tears because of elongated axial length and vitreous instability.<br><br>Hyperopia (A) is not a classic risk factor for retinal tears. Conjunctivitis (B), episcleritis (D), and chalazion (E) are anterior segment conditions unrelated to vitreoretinal degeneration.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dense vitreous hemorrhage cannot undergo fundus examination. Which investigation is most useful to detect retinal detachment?",o:["OCT","Fluorescein angiography","Schirmer test","Hess charting","B-scan ultrasonography"],a:4,e:"B-scan ultrasound can identify detached retina, vitreous hemorrhage, and posterior vitreous detachment even when media opacity prevents direct visualization.<br><br>This investigation is.<br><br>OCT (A) requires relatively clear ocular media. Fluorescein angiography (B) cannot adequately assess retina through dense hemorrhage. Hess charting (D) evaluates ocular motility disorders.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which postoperative complication most commonly causes recurrent retinal detachment after successful repair?",o:["Corneal hydrops","Episcleritis","Dacryocystitis","Papillitis","Proliferative vitreoretinopathy"],a:4,e:"Proliferative vitreoretinopathy (PVR) occurs when proliferative membranes form and contract over retinal surfaces, producing recurrent traction and redetachment.<br><br>PVR is considered the most important cause of failed retinal detachment surgery.<br><br>Corneal hydrops (A) occurs in keratoconus. Papillitis (D) affects the optic nerve. Episcleritis (B) and dacryocystitis (C) are unrelated anterior segment disorders.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment is most likely to occur after penetrating ocular trauma?",o:["Exudative only","Tractional only","Rhegmatogenous","Serous choroidal","Hypertensive retinal detachment"],a:2,e:"Penetrating trauma may produce retinal tears or dialysis, allowing liquefied vitreous to enter the subretinal space and create rhegmatogenous detachment.<br><br>Tractional detachments (B) arise from fibrovascular contraction rather than trauma-induced tears. Exudative detachments (A) result from fluid leakage without retinal breaks.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom combination most strongly indicates posterior vitreous detachment with possible retinal tear formation?",o:["Pain and redness","Halos with headache","Diplopia and ptosis","Watering and itching","Flashes and floaters"],a:4,e:"Flashes result from vitreoretinal traction stimulating the retina, while floaters occur from vitreous condensations or hemorrhage during posterior vitreous detachment.<br><br>This combination is considered an ophthalmic emergency warning sign because retinal tears may rapidly progress to retinal detachment.<br><br>Pain and redness (A) suggest inflammatory or glaucomatous disease. Diplopia and ptosis (C) indicate neurological or muscular pathology rather than retinal traction.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment surgery uses intravitreal gas tamponade combined with strict postoperative positioning?",o:["Scleral buckling","Vitrectomy only","Cyclocryotherapy","Trabeculectomy","Pneumatic retinopexy"],a:4,e:"Pneumatic retinopexy involves injection of intravitreal gas to tamponade retinal breaks while the patient maintains specific head positioning.<br><br>Scleral buckling (A) uses external scleral indentation rather than intravitreal gas alone. Trabeculectomy (D) is glaucoma surgery. Cyclocryotherapy (C) is not standard primary management.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal finding is highly suggestive of chronic retinal detachment?",o:["Intraretinal cysts","Macular drusen","Roth spots","Cherry-red spot","Optic disc edema"],a:0,e:"Long-standing retinal detachment may produce intraretinal cystic degeneration because chronic retinal separation causes progressive retinal atrophy.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (D) is characteristic of CRAO. Roth spots (C) occur in infective endocarditis or hematologic disorders. Drusen (B) are associated with ARMD.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding visual prognosis in retinal detachment is most accurate?",o:["Prognosis depends mainly on corneal status","Prognosis is identical in all cases","Macular involvement critically affects prognosis","Peripheral tears determine central acuity only","Visual recovery is impossible after surgery"],a:2,e:"Macular status is the most important prognostic factor because prolonged foveal separation damages photoreceptors and retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Urgent surgery before macular detachment offers the best visual outcome.<br><br>Corneal status (A) is not the principal prognostic determinant. Surgery can often successfully restore anatomy and useful vision, so option E is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which sign strongly indicates retinal tear in a patient with acute flashes and floaters?",o:["Bitot spots","Kayser-Fleischer ring","Hutchinson pupil","Argyll Robertson pupil","Shafer sign"],a:4,e:"Shafer sign refers to tobacco-dust retinal pigment epithelial cells suspended in the anterior vitreous, strongly indicating a retinal break or tear.<br><br>This sign is among the highest-yield emergency retina findings.<br><br>Bitot spots (A) occur in vitamin A deficiency. Kayser-Fleischer rings (B) are seen in Wilson disease. Argyll Robertson pupil (D) occurs in neurosyphilis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment type is most strongly associated with inflammatory choroidal disease?",o:["Rhegmatogenous","Tractional","Exudative","Giant tear detachment","Dialysis-related detachment"],a:2,e:"Inflammatory choroidal diseases increase vascular permeability and allow accumulation of subretinal fluid, producing exudative retinal detachment.<br><br>Examples include Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada disease and posterior scleritis.<br><br>Rhegmatogenous detachments (A) require retinal tears. Tractional detachments (B) occur from fibrovascular contraction rather than inflammatory exudation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal detachment configuration most commonly appears corrugated and undulating?",o:["Exudative","Tractional","Rhegmatogenous","Serous choroidal","Retinoschisis"],a:2,e:"Rhegmatogenous detachments classically appear corrugated because liquefied vitreous accumulates beneath mobile detached retina through retinal breaks.<br><br>Tractional detachments (B) usually appear concave because the retina is tethered inward. Exudative detachments (A) are smooth and bullous due to free-flowing subretinal fluid.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which patient profile has the greatest risk of postoperative retinal detachment?",o:["Young hyperopic patient","Elderly high myope after cataract surgery","Chronic blepharitis patient","Episcleritis patient","Allergic conjunctivitis patient"],a:1,e:"High myopia, aging vitreous degeneration, and cataract surgery together markedly increase risk for retinal tears and rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Blepharitis (C), episcleritis (D), and allergic conjunctivitis (E) are anterior segment inflammatory conditions unrelated to retinal tear formation. Hyperopia (A) is not a major RRD risk factor.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which mechanism best explains visual field defect progression in retinal detachment?",o:["Corneal edema expansion","Optic nerve infarction","Choroidal ischemia alone","Lens opacity enlargement","Progressive retinal separation from RPE"],a:4,e:"As retinal detachment enlarges, progressively greater retinal areas lose functional contact with the retinal pigment epithelium, producing expanding visual field defects.<br><br>Patients classically describe a spreading curtain or shadow corresponding to the advancing detached retina.<br><br>Corneal edema (A) causes generalized blur and halos rather than curtain-like field defects. Lens opacity (D) reduces clarity diffusely but does not produce progressive field shadows. Optic nerve infarction (B) produces different visual field patterns.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 3-year-old child presents with leukocoria and strabismus in the right eye. Fundoscopy reveals a creamy white retinal mass with calcification. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Coats disease","Choroidal melanoma","Persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous"],a:0,e:"Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy of childhood and classically presents with leukocoria and strabismus. Calcification within the retinal mass is a highly characteristic imaging feature.<br><br>The tumor originates from primitive retinal cells and may be hereditary or sporadic.<br><br>Coats disease (C) may mimic leukocoria but typically demonstrates telangiectatic retinal vessels and exudation rather than calcified retinal tumors. Choroidal melanoma (D) occurs predominantly in adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which gene mutation is classically associated with retinoblastoma?",o:["PAX6","ABCA4","BEST1","MYOC","RB1"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma results from mutation of the RB1 tumor suppressor gene located on chromosome 13q14. The hereditary form follows the \"two-hit hypothesis.\"<br><br>Children with germline mutations often develop bilateral multifocal tumors and carry increased risk of secondary malignancies later in life.<br><br>BEST1 mutations (C) are associated with Best disease, while MYOC mutations (D) are linked to juvenile glaucoma. ABCA4 mutations (B) are characteristic of Stargardt disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical feature is the commonest presenting sign of retinoblastoma?",o:["Painful red eye","Epiphora","Diplopia","Proptosis","Leukocoria"],a:4,e:"Leukocoria, or white pupillary reflex, is the most common presenting feature of retinoblastoma and results from reflection of light from the tumor mass.<br><br>Parents often first notice the abnormal reflex in photographs.<br><br>Painful red eye (A) usually appears later in advanced disease with secondary glaucoma. Proptosis (D) suggests orbital extension rather than early intraocular disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation most classically demonstrates intraocular calcification in retinoblastoma?",o:["OCT","Fundus fluorescein angiography","CT scan orbit","Schirmer test","Hess charting"],a:2,e:"CT scan classically demonstrates intraocular calcification, which strongly supports the diagnosis of retinoblastoma. Calcification is one of the hallmark radiologic findings.<br><br>Although MRI is increasingly preferred for optic nerve and intracranial assessment, CT historically remains a classic recall association for calcification detection.<br><br>OCT (A) mainly evaluates retinal layers. Fluorescein angiography (B) is not the standard test for identifying tumor calcification. Schirmer testing (D) evaluates tear production.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral retinoblastoma most strongly suggests:",o:["Sporadic mutation","Metastatic disease only","Benign retinal hamartoma","Infectious retinitis","Hereditary disease"],a:4,e:"Bilateral retinoblastoma is strongly associated with germline RB1 mutation and hereditary disease. These patients often develop multifocal tumors at younger ages.<br><br>Hereditary retinoblastoma also carries increased risk of secondary malignancies such as osteosarcoma.<br><br>Sporadic disease (A) is more commonly unilateral. Infectious retinitis (D) and benign hamartomas (C) do not produce bilateral malignant calcified retinal tumors.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most strongly associated with tuberous sclerosis?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Hemangioblastoma","Medulloepithelioma"],a:2,e:"Retinal astrocytomas are benign glial tumors strongly associated with tuberous sclerosis and may appear as elevated calcified retinal lesions.<br><br>These lesions are often asymptomatic and discovered during routine examination.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) is associated with RB1 mutation rather than tuberous sclerosis. Hemangioblastoma (D) is classically linked to von Hippel-Lindau disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular tumor is classically associated with von Hippel-Lindau disease?",o:["Retinal astrocytoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal nevus","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Medulloepithelioma"],a:3,e:"Retinal hemangioblastoma (retinal capillary hemangioma) is strongly associated with von Hippel-Lindau syndrome and may occur with CNS hemangioblastomas or renal tumors.<br><br>These vascular tumors may produce exudation, retinal detachment, and visual loss if untreated.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (A) is associated with tuberous sclerosis rather than VHL disease. Retinoblastoma (B) is linked to RB1 mutation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with advanced retinoblastoma develops painful red eye and elevated intraocular pressure. Which complication is most likely responsible?",o:["Acute conjunctivitis","Secondary glaucoma","Corneal dystrophy","Episcleritis","Retinal migraine"],a:1,e:"Advanced retinoblastoma may obstruct aqueous outflow or invade anterior structures, causing secondary glaucoma with painful red eye and elevated intraocular pressure.<br><br>Pain usually indicates advanced disease and poor prognosis.<br><br>Acute conjunctivitis (A) does not explain intraocular tumor-related glaucoma. Episcleritis (D) causes mild discomfort rather than severe pressure elevation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which treatment modality is commonly used for small peripheral retinoblastoma lesions?",o:["Cycloplegia only","DCR","Trabeculectomy","Penetrating keratoplasty","Laser photocoagulation or cryotherapy"],a:4,e:"Small peripheral retinoblastoma lesions may be treated with focal therapies such as laser photocoagulation or cryotherapy to preserve vision and globe integrity.<br><br>Modern retinoblastoma management increasingly uses globe-salvaging strategies alongside systemic or intra-arterial chemotherapy.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (C) is contraindicated in intraocular malignancy because of risk of tumor spread. Keratoplasty (D) and DCR (B) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly differentiates Coats disease from retinoblastoma?",o:["Leukocoria","Unilateral presentation","Exudative retinal detachment","Childhood onset","Presence of retinal telangiectasia without calcification"],a:4,e:"Coats disease classically demonstrates retinal telangiectatic vessels with heavy exudation and usually lacks calcification, helping differentiate it from retinoblastoma.<br><br>Both conditions may present with leukocoria in childhood, making imaging and careful fundus examination essential.<br><br>Leukocoria (A), unilateral disease (B), and childhood onset (D) may occur in both conditions and therefore are less specific differentiators.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which route of spread is most feared in advanced retinoblastoma?",o:["Corneal spread only","Episcleral spread only","Lacrimal sac invasion","Conjunctival dissemination only","Optic nerve extension"],a:4,e:"Optic nerve invasion is a major poor prognostic factor because it allows intracranial spread of retinoblastoma.<br><br>MRI is particularly valuable for evaluating optic nerve involvement.<br><br>Corneal spread (A) is uncommon compared with optic nerve invasion. Lacrimal sac invasion (C) is not the classic route of life-threatening dissemination.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which age group is most commonly affected by retinoblastoma?",o:["Elderly adults","Neonates only","Children younger than 5 years","Teenagers only","Middle-aged adults"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma predominantly affects young children, usually presenting before the age of five years.<br><br>Early diagnosis is critical because delayed treatment may result in optic nerve invasion, metastasis, or death.<br><br>Retinoblastoma is extremely uncommon in adults (A, E). Teenage presentation (D) is unusual and should prompt reconsideration of diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is preferred for evaluating optic nerve and intracranial extension in retinoblastoma?",o:["OCT","MRI","Schirmer testing","Keratometry","Pachymetry"],a:1,e:"MRI provides excellent soft tissue detail and is preferred for evaluating optic nerve invasion and intracranial extension in retinoblastoma.<br><br>It avoids ionizing radiation exposure and is therefore favored over CT in many pediatric oncology settings.<br><br>OCT (A) evaluates retinal microstructure rather than orbital extension. Keratometry (D) and pachymetry (E) assess corneal parameters only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor may appear as a mulberry-like calcified lesion associated with tuberous sclerosis?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Medulloepithelioma","Choroidal melanoma","Hemangioblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma"],a:4,e:"Retinal astrocytomas often appear as whitish calcified \"mulberry-like\" lesions and are strongly associated with tuberous sclerosis.<br><br>These tumors are generally benign but recognition is important because of systemic neurological associations.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) is malignant and usually presents with leukocoria in very young children. Hemangioblastomas (D) are vascular tumors associated with von Hippel-Lindau syndrome.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which hereditary syndrome is classically associated with retinal capillary hemangioma?",o:["Marfan syndrome","Sturge-Weber syndrome","Wilson disease","Neurofibromatosis type 2","Von Hippel,Lindau disease"],a:4,e:"Retinal capillary hemangiomas are characteristic ocular manifestations of von Hippel-Lindau disease and may occur alongside CNS hemangioblastomas or renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Marfan syndrome (A) mainly causes ectopia lentis. Wilson disease (C) produces Kayser-Fleischer rings rather than retinal vascular tumors.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which management option is generally preferred for advanced unilateral retinoblastoma with poor visual potential?",o:["Observation only","Corneal transplantation","LASIK surgery","Trabeculectomy","Enucleation"],a:4,e:"Enucleation is preferred for advanced unilateral retinoblastoma with minimal visual potential to prevent metastatic spread and save life.<br><br>Life preservation remains the primary management goal in advanced retinoblastoma. Globe salvage is considered only when oncologically safe.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (D) is contraindicated because it may facilitate tumor spread. LASIK (C) and corneal transplantation (B) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor most commonly presents with exudative retinal detachment due to vascular leakage?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal nevus","Retinal astrocytoma","Combined hamartoma"],a:0,e:"Retinal hemangioblastomas are highly vascular tumors that frequently produce exudation and secondary exudative retinal detachment.<br><br>Visual loss often results from chronic leakage and macular involvement rather than direct tumor invasion alone.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) primarily presents with leukocoria and calcified retinal masses. Retinal astrocytomas (D) are glial lesions less commonly associated with marked exudation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature is considered a poor prognostic sign in retinoblastoma histopathology?",o:["Tumor calcification","Choroidal invasion","Retinal edema only","Peripheral tumor location","Mild vitreous haze"],a:1,e:"Choroidal invasion and optic nerve invasion are major histopathological risk factors because they increase risk of systemic dissemination and metastasis.<br><br>Histopathologic examination after enucleation is therefore critical for staging and planning additional therapy.<br><br>Tumor calcification (A) is characteristic but not itself a major poor prognostic sign. Mild vitreous haze (E) does not strongly predict metastasis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is benign and derived from glial tissue?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Retinal lymphoma","Choroidal melanoma","Medulloepithelioma","Retinal astrocytoma"],a:4,e:"Retinal astrocytoma is a benign glial tumor arising from retinal astrocytes and commonly associated with tuberous sclerosis.<br><br>These lesions are often calcified and relatively stable, although occasional progression may occur.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) is malignant embryonal retinal tumor. Choroidal melanoma (C) arises from melanocytes rather than glial tissue.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding hereditary retinoblastoma is most accurate?",o:["It is always unilateral","It carries no systemic cancer risk","It commonly presents later in adulthood","It is associated with increased risk of secondary malignancies","It never involves both eyes"],a:3,e:"Patients with hereditary retinoblastoma possess germline RB1 mutations and therefore have increased risk of secondary malignancies, particularly osteosarcoma and soft tissue sarcomas.<br><br>Long-term surveillance is therefore essential even after successful ocular treatment.<br><br>Hereditary retinoblastoma is often bilateral, so options A and E are incorrect. Adult presentation (C) is uncommon because the disease primarily affects young children.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with unilateral leukocoria. CT orbit demonstrates intraocular calcification. Which diagnosis should be considered first?",o:["Coats disease","Persistent fetal vasculature","Toxocariasis","Congenital cataract","Retinoblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma is the most important cause of leukocoria associated with intraocular calcification in children. CT findings of calcified retinal mass are highly characteristic.<br><br>Coats disease (A) may produce leukocoria but usually lacks calcification. Congenital cataract (D) causes leukocoria without intraocular tumor formation. Persistent fetal vasculature (B) demonstrates fibrovascular stalk rather than calcified retinal mass.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which hereditary syndrome is most strongly associated with bilateral multifocal retinoblastoma?",o:["Von Hippel,Lindau disease","Marfan syndrome","Sturge-Weber syndrome","Neurofibromatosis type 1","Germline RB1 mutation syndrome"],a:4,e:"Bilateral multifocal retinoblastoma strongly suggests hereditary disease caused by germline RB1 mutation. These patients often present earlier and have multiple retinal tumors.<br><br>Such patients also possess increased risk of secondary malignancies later in life.<br><br>Von Hippel-Lindau disease (A) is associated with retinal hemangioblastoma rather than retinoblastoma. Sturge-Weber syndrome (C) primarily involves choroidal hemangioma and facial nevus flammeus.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly differentiates Coats disease from retinoblastoma in a child with leukocoria?",o:["Male predominance","Childhood presentation","Presence of retinal telangiectasia and absence of calcification","Exudative retinal detachment","Unilateral disease"],a:2,e:"Coats disease demonstrates abnormal retinal telangiectatic vessels with heavy lipid exudation and usually lacks calcification, helping differentiate it from retinoblastoma.<br><br>Unilateral disease (E) and childhood onset (B) may occur in both conditions. Exudative retinal detachment (D) is also possible in both advanced Coats disease and retinoblastoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which route of spread is considered the most dangerous in advanced retinoblastoma?",o:["Corneal spread","Optic nerve invasion","Lens capsule invasion","Lacrimal gland extension","Episcleral pigmentation"],a:1,e:"Optic nerve invasion is a critical poor prognostic factor because it permits intracranial spread of retinoblastoma and markedly increases metastatic risk.<br><br>MRI evaluation of optic nerve extension is therefore essential in staging advanced disease.<br><br>Corneal spread (A) is uncommon and less prognostically significant. Lens capsule invasion (C) does not carry the same systemic dissemination risk as optic nerve involvement.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with advanced retinoblastoma develops painful red eye and elevated intraocular pressure. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Episcleritis","Keratoconus","Optic neuritis","Acute conjunctivitis","Secondary glaucoma"],a:4,e:"Advanced retinoblastoma may obstruct aqueous outflow pathways or invade anterior segment structures, causing secondary glaucoma with pain and elevated intraocular pressure.<br><br>Painful red eye in a child with leukocoria should always raise suspicion of advanced retinoblastoma.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) causes relatively mild discomfort without intraocular malignancy. Optic neuritis (C) causes painful visual loss rather than leukocoria with intraocular mass.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal vascular tumor is classically associated with von Hippel-Lindau disease?",o:["Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinoblastoma","Medulloepithelioma"],a:2,e:"Retinal hemangioblastomas are vascular retinal tumors strongly associated with von Hippel-Lindau disease and may coexist with cerebellar hemangioblastomas or renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>These lesions may cause exudation, retinal detachment, and visual loss if untreated.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (A) is associated with tuberous sclerosis rather than VHL disease. Retinoblastoma (D) arises from RB1 mutations.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is strongly associated with tuberous sclerosis?",o:["Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal nevus","Retinoblastoma","Retinal lymphoma","Choroidal osteoma"],a:0,e:"Retinal astrocytoma is a benign glial retinal tumor frequently associated with tuberous sclerosis. It often appears as a whitish calcified \"mulberry-like\" lesion.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (C) is associated with RB1 mutation rather than tuberous sclerosis. Choroidal osteoma (E) is an ossifying choridal lesion unrelated to tuberous sclerosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is preferred for evaluating optic nerve extension in retinoblastoma?",o:["B-scan ultrasonography","Hess charting","Keratometry","OCT only","MRI orbit and brain"],a:4,e:"MRI provides superior soft tissue resolution and is preferred for detecting optic nerve invasion and intracranial extension in retinoblastoma.<br><br>It avoids ionizing radiation exposure and is therefore preferred in many pediatric oncology settings.<br><br>B-scan ultrasound (A) is useful for intraocular mass detection but less sensitive for optic nerve extension. Keratometry (C) evaluates corneal curvature only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which management option is preferred for advanced unilateral retinoblastoma with no useful visual potential?",o:["Observation","Keratoplasty","LASIK","Trabeculectomy","Enucleation"],a:4,e:"Enucleation is preferred in advanced unilateral retinoblastoma when globe salvage is not feasible and visual prognosis is poor. The primary goal remains life preservation.<br><br>Histopathological evaluation after enucleation helps identify optic nerve or choroidal invasion.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (D) is contraindicated in intraocular malignancy because of risk of extraocular spread. LASIK (C) and keratoplasty (B) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature is considered a poor prognostic histopathological sign in retinoblastoma?",o:["Tumor calcification","Choroidal invasion","Mild vitreous haze","Peripheral retinal location","Cataract formation"],a:1,e:"Choroidal invasion significantly increases the risk of metastatic dissemination and is considered an important poor prognostic factor in retinoblastoma.<br><br>Histopathological examination after enucleation therefore plays a critical role in postoperative risk stratification and adjuvant therapy decisions.<br><br>Calcification (A) is characteristic but not itself a poor prognostic feature. Mild vitreous haze (C) does not strongly predict metastatic spread.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor most commonly presents with leukocoria in infancy?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Combined hamartoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinoblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma is the commonest primary intraocular malignancy of childhood and classically presents with leukocoria in infancy or early childhood.<br><br>Parents frequently notice abnormal white reflex in flash photography.<br><br>Choroidal melanoma (D) occurs mainly in adults. Retinal astrocytoma (B) is usually benign and often asymptomatic.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor may produce exudative retinal detachment due to marked vascular leakage?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal nevus","Retinoschisis"],a:0,e:"Retinal hemangioblastomas are highly vascular tumors that frequently leak fluid and lipids, producing exudative retinal detachment and visual impairment.<br><br>Untreated lesions may eventually cause severe secondary retinal damage.<br><br>Retinoschisis (E) represents splitting of retinal layers rather than vascular tumor exudation. Choroidal nevus (D) is usually asymptomatic and minimally exudative.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which age group is most commonly affected by retinoblastoma?",o:["Elderly adults","Teenagers only","Children younger than 5 years","Middle-aged adults","Neonates exclusively"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma primarily affects young children, most commonly presenting before five years of age. Early diagnosis is critical for globe and life preservation.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis may lead to optic nerve invasion, orbital spread, and intracranial dissemination.<br><br>Adult retinoblastoma is extremely rare. Neonatal-only presentation (E) is incorrect because most cases present during infancy and early childhood.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is benign and glial in origin?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Medulloepithelioma","Retinal lymphoma"],a:2,e:"Retinal astrocytoma is a benign glial tumor derived from retinal astrocytes and commonly associated with tuberous sclerosis.<br><br>It often demonstrates calcification and mulberry-like appearance but usually progresses slowly. Recognition is important because of systemic neurological associations.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) is a malignant embryonal retinal tumor. Choroidal melanoma (A) arises from melanocytes rather than glial cells.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical presentation is highly suspicious for retinoblastoma in a young child?",o:["Painful watering eye only","Sudden diplopia","Progressive ptosis only","Episcleritis","Leukocoria with strabismus"],a:4,e:"Leukocoria and strabismus are the two most common presenting features of retinoblastoma. Strabismus develops because macular involvement impairs fixation.<br><br>Diplopia (B) is uncommon in very young children with retinoblastoma. Episcleritis (D) and ptosis (C) do not characteristically indicate intraocular malignancy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor may appear as a calcified mulberry-like lesion during fundoscopy?",o:["Retinal astrocytoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Choroidal metastasis"],a:0,e:"Retinal astrocytomas often appear as whitish calcified mulberry-like lesions because of glial proliferation and calcification.<br><br>They are strongly associated with tuberous sclerosis and frequently discovered incidentally during fundus examination.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) may also calcify but usually presents as malignant retinal mass with leukocoria in young children rather than classic mulberry lesion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding hereditary retinoblastoma is most accurate?",o:["It is always unilateral","It lacks systemic cancer risk","It commonly presents in adulthood","It is associated with secondary malignancies","It never involves both eyes"],a:3,e:"Hereditary retinoblastoma patients possess germline RB1 mutations and therefore have increased lifetime risk of secondary malignancies such as osteosarcoma.<br><br>Long-term follow-up remains essential even after successful ocular treatment.<br><br>Hereditary disease is often bilateral, making options A and E incorrect. Adult presentation (C) is highly unusual.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most strongly associated with retinal telangiectasia and massive exudation?",o:["Coats disease","Retinal astrocytoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal lymphoma"],a:0,e:"Coats disease demonstrates abnormal retinal telangiectatic vessels with heavy exudation that may eventually produce exudative retinal detachment and leukocoria.<br><br>Differentiation from retinoblastoma is crucial because management and prognosis differ dramatically. Lack of calcification is an important clue.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (B) is glial and calcified rather than telangiectatic. Retinoblastoma (C) typically demonstrates intraocular calcification.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly favors retinoblastoma over persistent fetal vasculature?",o:["Leukocoria","Childhood onset","Presence of calcification","Unilateral involvement","Reduced vision"],a:2,e:"Calcification strongly favors retinoblastoma because persistent fetal vasculature usually lacks calcified intraocular masses.<br><br>Both conditions may produce leukocoria and unilateral visual impairment in infancy, making imaging critically important.<br><br>Reduced vision (E) and unilateral presentation (D) may occur in both disorders and therefore are less discriminatory.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor management principle has the highest priority?",o:["Cosmetic preservation only","Avoiding chemotherapy entirely","LASIK before treatment","Cataract extraction before tumor therapy","Preservation of life first, then globe and vision"],a:4,e:"In retinal tumors such as retinoblastoma, the highest priority is life preservation, followed by globe salvage and finally visual preservation when oncologically safe.<br><br>Modern treatment strategies increasingly attempt globe salvage through chemotherapy and focal therapies, but metastatic prevention remains paramount.<br><br>Cosmetic preservation alone (A) is insufficient in malignant disease. LASIK (C) and cataract extraction (D) are unrelated to primary tumor management priorities.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 2-year-old child presents with leukocoria, strabismus, and vitreous seeding seen on fundoscopy. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Persistent fetal vasculature","Coats disease","Retinoblastoma","Congenital cataract","Retinopathy of prematurity"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma classically presents with leukocoria and strabismus in early childhood. Vitreous seeding strongly supports intraocular malignant retinal tumor spread and is considered an important staging feature.<br><br>Persistent fetal vasculature (A) may produce leukocoria but usually demonstrates fibrovascular stalk rather than vitreous tumor seeds. Coats disease (B) typically shows telangiectatic retinal vessels with exudation rather than malignant vitreous dissemination.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which chromosomal abnormality is classically associated with retinoblastoma?",o:["Chromosome 7q deletion","Chromosome 5q deletion","Chromosome 21 trisomy","Chromosome 11p mutation","Chromosome 13q14 deletion"],a:4,e:"The RB1 tumor suppressor gene is located on chromosome 13q14, and mutations or deletions at this site are strongly associated with retinoblastoma.<br><br>Chromosome 11p mutations (D) are associated with Wilms tumor. Trisomy 21 (C) is associated with Down syndrome rather than retinal malignancy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor most commonly presents with a yellow-orange vascular retinal mass and dilated feeder vessels?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Retinal lymphoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinal hemangioblastoma characteristically appears as a vascular retinal mass with markedly dilated feeder and draining vessels.<br><br>These tumors are strongly associated with von Hippel-Lindau disease and may produce exudation and retinal detachment if untreated.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (C) is usually whitish and calcified rather than highly vascular. Retinoblastoma (A) generally presents as pale retinal mass with calcification in young children.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical feature most strongly suggests extraocular extension of retinoblastoma?",o:["Leukocoria","Strabismus","Photophobia","Vitreous floaters","Proptosis"],a:4,e:"Proptosis in retinoblastoma strongly suggests orbital extension and advanced disease. This finding carries poor prognosis because extraocular spread increases metastatic risk significantly.<br><br>Orbital invasion is considered a late and dangerous manifestation.<br><br>Leukocoria (A) and strabismus (B) are common early intraocular presentations rather than signs of orbital extension. Floaters (D) are uncommon presenting complaints in young children.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most strongly associated with exudative retinal detachment in children without calcification?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Coats disease","Choroidal nevus","Medulloepithelioma"],a:2,e:"Coats disease causes abnormal retinal telangiectasia and heavy lipid exudation that may progress to exudative retinal detachment and leukocoria.<br><br>Absence of calcification helps distinguish it from retinoblastoma, making this one of the classic pediatric retina differential diagnosis recalls.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) usually demonstrates calcification. Retinal astrocytoma (B) is glial and typically associated with tuberous sclerosis rather than massive vascular exudation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which secondary malignancy is classically associated with hereditary retinoblastoma survivors?",o:["Osteosarcoma","Glioblastoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Thyroid carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],a:0,e:"Patients with hereditary retinoblastoma possess germline RB1 mutations and carry markedly increased risk of secondary malignancies, especially osteosarcoma.<br><br>Long-term surveillance is therefore essential even after successful ocular treatment.<br><br>Glioblastoma (B) and thyroid carcinoma (D) are not the classic secondary malignancies associated with RB1 mutation carriers.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor may appear as a translucent elevated lesion with calcified nodules in tuberous sclerosis?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Choroidal osteoma","Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma"],a:4,e:"Retinal astrocytomas are benign glial tumors associated with tuberous sclerosis and may appear as translucent lesions that later calcify into mulberry-like masses.<br><br>Recognition of ocular manifestations may facilitate diagnosis of systemic neurological disease.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (D) is malignant and typically occurs in much younger children with leukocoria. Choroidal osteoma (C) is a calcified choroidal lesion rather than retinal glial tumor.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which treatment modality is increasingly used for globe salvage in retinoblastoma?",o:["Panretinal photocoagulation only","Intra-arterial chemotherapy","Trabeculectomy","Penetrating keratoplasty","Cyclodialysis"],a:1,e:"Intra-arterial chemotherapy delivers chemotherapeutic agents directly through the ophthalmic artery and has become an important globe-salvaging therapy for retinoblastoma.<br><br>Modern management increasingly emphasizes eye preservation when oncologically safe.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (C) is contraindicated in intraocular malignancy because of risk of tumor dissemination. Keratoplasty (D) is unrelated to retinal tumors.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which finding most strongly favors persistent fetal vasculature over retinoblastoma?",o:["Leukocoria","Childhood onset","Retrolental fibrovascular stalk","Reduced visual acuity","Unilateral disease"],a:2,e:"Persistent fetal vasculature classically demonstrates a retrolental fibrovascular stalk extending from the optic disc toward the posterior lens capsule.<br><br>This congenital anomaly is a classic differential diagnosis of retinoblastoma in pediatric leukocoria questions.<br><br>Leukocoria (A) and unilateral disease (E) may occur in both disorders. Reduced vision (D) is nonspecific and therefore less discriminatory.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular tumor is the most common primary intraocular malignancy of childhood?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Medulloepithelioma","Astrocytoma","Retinal lymphoma","Retinoblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma is the commonest primary intraocular malignancy in children and represents a major ophthalmic emergency because delayed treatment may be fatal.<br><br>Early recognition of leukocoria and prompt referral dramatically improve survival outcomes.<br><br>Choroidal melanoma (A) is the commonest primary intraocular malignancy in adults, not children. Retinal astrocytoma (C) is benign rather than malignant.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most strongly associated with cerebellar hemangioblastoma?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Combined hamartoma"],a:0,e:"Retinal hemangioblastoma is part of von Hippel-Lindau disease, which also predisposes to cerebellar hemangioblastomas and renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Recognition of retinal vascular tumors should therefore prompt systemic evaluation.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (B) is linked to tuberous sclerosis rather than VHL syndrome. Retinoblastoma (C) is associated with RB1 mutation instead.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature is considered most characteristic of retinoblastoma on histopathology?",o:["Verocay bodies","Psammoma bodies","Lisch nodules","Touton giant cells","Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes"],a:4,e:"Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes are characteristic histopathological structures seen in retinoblastoma and reflect primitive retinal differentiation.<br><br>Verocay bodies (A) are associated with schwannoma. Psammoma bodies (B) are commonly associated with meningioma and papillary thyroid carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor most commonly causes vitreous seeding?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Choroidal nevus","Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal osteoma"],a:2,e:"Vitreous seeding is a classic feature of advanced retinoblastoma and significantly complicates treatment because tumor cells disseminate throughout the vitreous cavity.<br><br>Recognition of vitreous seeds is important in staging and treatment planning.<br><br>Retinal astrocytoma (D) is benign and typically does not produce vitreous tumor seeding. Choroidal osteoma (E) is a benign ossifying lesion unrelated to vitreous dissemination.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most likely to produce feeder vessels visible clinically?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinoblastoma","Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal metastasis","Choroidal nevus"],a:0,e:"Retinal hemangioblastomas characteristically demonstrate prominent feeder and draining retinal vessels because of their vascular nature.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) generally presents as whitish retinal mass with calcification rather than prominent vascular feeder channels.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding sporadic retinoblastoma is most accurate?",o:["It is usually bilateral","It commonly presents with multifocal tumors","It always involves optic nerve invasion","It carries very high secondary malignancy risk","It is typically unilateral"],a:4,e:"Sporadic retinoblastoma is usually unilateral and unifocal because both RB1 mutations occur somatically within a single retinal cell line.<br><br>Bilateral multifocal disease (A, B) strongly suggests hereditary germline RB1 mutation. Secondary malignancy risk (D) is much higher in hereditary disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is benign but may still cause exudation and retinal detachment?",o:["Retinal hemangioblastoma","Retinoblastoma","Retinal lymphoma","Choroidal melanoma","Medulloepithelioma"],a:0,e:"Retinal hemangioblastoma is histologically benign but can cause significant visual morbidity because of vascular leakage, exudation, and retinal detachment.<br><br>Visual loss often results from secondary retinal damage rather than malignant invasion itself.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) and choroidal melanoma (D) are malignant tumors. Retinal lymphoma (C) is infiltrative rather than vascular.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical sign is most strongly associated with advanced retinoblastoma rather than early disease?",o:["Leukocoria","Strabismus","Proptosis","Abnormal red reflex","Mild visual reduction"],a:2,e:"Proptosis suggests extraocular extension of retinoblastoma and therefore represents advanced disease with poor prognosis.<br><br>This sign indicates possible orbital invasion and increased metastatic risk.<br><br>Leukocoria (A) and abnormal red reflex (D) are common early presentations. Strabismus (B) may occur relatively early because of macular involvement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal tumor is most strongly linked to chromosome 13 abnormalities?",o:["Retinal astrocytoma","Choroidal osteoma","Retinal hemangioblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Retinoblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma is strongly associated with chromosome 13q14 abnormalities involving the RB1 tumor suppressor gene.<br><br>Retinal hemangioblastoma (C) is associated with VHL gene abnormalities on chromosome 3 rather than chromosome 13.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which management principle is contraindicated in suspected retinoblastoma because of risk of tumor dissemination?",o:["Laser photocoagulation","Cryotherapy","Trabeculectomy","Chemotherapy","Enucleation"],a:2,e:"Trabeculectomy is contraindicated in retinoblastoma because fistulizing surgery may facilitate extraocular tumor spread and worsen prognosis.<br><br>Cryotherapy (B) and laser photocoagulation (A) may be used for small tumors. Enucleation (E) remains appropriate in advanced unilateral disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with bilateral multifocal retinoblastoma survives treatment successfully. Which long-term complication requires continued surveillance most importantly?",o:["Chronic dacryocystitis","Secondary non-ocular malignancies","Corneal ectasia","Cataract only","Episcleritis"],a:1,e:"Children with hereditary bilateral retinoblastoma possess germline RB1 mutations and therefore remain at lifelong risk for secondary malignancies, especially osteosarcoma and soft tissue sarcomas.<br><br>Long-term oncologic surveillance is therefore essential even after successful ocular tumor control.<br><br>Chronic dacryocystitis (A) and episcleritis (E) are unrelated to RB1 mutation syndromes. Cataract formation (D) is less critical than systemic malignancy risk.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
];